ative Songs chart, but peaked at number 12 on the Alternative Digital Songs chart.<ref name=\"US-Alternative-digital-singles\" />}}\n| \u2014{{efn|group=upper-alpha|\"Mine Is Yours\" did not enter the Rock Songs chart, but peaked at number 24 on the Rock Digital Songs chart.<ref name=\"US-Digital\" />}}\n| ''Mine Is Yours''\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-ua|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.coldwarkids.com}}\n\n{{Cold War Kids}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American blues rock musical groups]]\n[[Category:Biola University]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Indie rock musical groups from California]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2004]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:MapleMusic Recordings artists]]\n[[Category:V2 Records artists]]\n[[Category:Downtown Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Happyomen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSingles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cold_War_Kids"}
{"title_page": "Hozier (musician)", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish musician}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Hozier\n| image            = Hozier 2015 01 (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Hozier in 2015\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Andrew John Hozier-Byrne\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1990|3|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bray, County Wicklow]], Ireland\n| module={{Infobox person|embed=yes\n| parents          = John Byrne, Raine Hozier-Byrne}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar}}<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| genre            = {{hlist| [[Blues]]|[[indie rock]]|[[Soul Music|soul]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Folk music|folk]]|[[blues rock]]|[[indie pop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|singer|songwriter}}\n| years_active     = 2008\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Rubyworks Records|Rubyworks]]|[[Island Records|Island]]|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]}}\n| associated_acts  = [[Mavis Staples]]\n<br>[[Angie McMahon]]<ref> Hutchingson, John. \u201cPhoto Gallery: Hozier and Angie McMahon Live in Boston.\u201d Boston News, Vanyaland, 13 Nov. 2019, vanyaland.com/2019/11/13/photo-gallery-hozier-and-angie-mcmahon-live-in-boston/.\n</ref>\n| website          = {{url|hozier.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrew John Hozier-Byrne''' (born 17 March 1990), known professionally as '''Hozier''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|o\u028a|z|i|\u0259r}} {{respell|HOH|zee|\u0259r}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://1079ishot.com/how-do-you-pronounce-hozier/|title=How Do You Pronounce Hozier?|publisher=HOT 107.9|accessdate=30 September 2018|date=28 January 2015}}</ref>), is an Irish musician, singer, and songwriter from [[County Wicklow]]. He had his international breakthrough after releasing his debut single \"[[Take Me to Church]]\", which has been certified multi-platinum in several countries, including the US, the UK, and Canada.\n\nIn 2013, he released his debut EP, featuring the single \"Take Me to Church\". His [[Hozier (album)|debut studio album]], released in 2014, topped the chart in Ireland and scored top ten positions on global charts. It has been certified 6\u00d7 platinum in Ireland and multi-platinum in several countries. He embarked on an American and a European tour to support the album.\n\nIn September 2018, Hozier released an EP, titled ''[[Nina Cried Power]]'', featuring the title track as a single. He released his second album, ''[[Wasteland, Baby!]]'', in March 2019. It debuted atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and was followed by a tour to promote it.\n\n== Early life ==\nHozier was born in [[Bray, County Wicklow|Bray]], [[County Wicklow]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/6059764/hozier/biography| title=Hozier - Biography |publisher=Billboard.com |accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/meet-the-bray-singer-cracking-america-30089463.html | title=Meet the Bray singer cracking America |publisher=Irish Independent |date=13 March 2014|accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref>; and grew up in the Irish countryside, near the village [[Delgany]]. <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/behind-hoziers-unlikely-rise-60949/ | title=Behind Hozier's Unlikely Rise| date=29 January 2015}}</ref> \nHozier's father, John Byrne, is a local [[blues]] drummer whose day job was working at a bank; while his mother, Raine Hozier-Byrne, is an artist.<ref name=\"propelling\">Smyth, David (6 June 2014). \"[https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/religious-abuse-homophobia-and-singing-corpses-are-the-unlikely-ingredients-propelling-hozier-to-9499292.html Religious abuse, homophobia and singing corpses are the unlikely ingredients propelling Hozier to rock stardom]\". ''Go London''.</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/hozier-if-i-wanted-to-make-a-f-king-pop-song-i-would-1.3794161?mode=amp|title=Hozier: 'If I wanted to make a f**king pop song, I would'|last=Bruton|first=Louise|date=23 February 2019|website=The Irish Times|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>\n\nHozier and his brother, Jon, were raised in the Protestant [[Quakers|Quaker]] faith.<ref name=\"propelling\" /> He now identifies as [[agnostic]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/behind-hoziers-unlikely-rise-60949/ | title=Behind Hozier's Unlikely Rise| date=29 January 2015}}</ref> He has been writing songs since the age of 15.<ref name=\"adored\" /> He attended Delgany National School and [[St. Gerard's School]] before he began studying music in [[Trinity College, Dublin]]. He was refused a year's deferral by the college after missing exams to record demos for a music label.<ref name=\"searing\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://issuu.com/osnovina/docs/issuu_9-1|title=Go Rail 9-1: Featuring Hozier |last=Mullally |first=Una |date=14 October 2013<!--|website=issuu.com-->|website=The Irish Times}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Beginnings===\nWhile in Trinity, Hozier became involved with the Trinity Orchestra. He was a member of the choral ensemble [[An\u00fana]] from 2007 to 2012 and appears as a soloist on their 2014 release ''Illuminations'' singing \"[[Courir de Mardi Gras#La Chanson de Mardi Gras|La Chanson de Mardi Gras]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anuna.ie/timeline|title=Our Story|website=AN\u00daNA|accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref> He toured and sang with the group internationally including performances in Norway and the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|author=Anna Job |url=http://www.goldenplec.com/hozier-interview/ |title=Hozier &#124; Interview |website=Goldenplec.com |date=1 August 2013|accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref> Hozier played at [[Oxegen|Oxegen Festival]] in [[Oxegen 2009|2009]]<ref>\"The Line-up\". ''Irish Times'' (Dublin). 10 July 2009.</ref> and [[Oxegen 2010|2010]].<ref>\"Line-up\". ''The Sun'' (London). July 7, 2010B. p. 4, 5.</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132016: ''Take Me to Church'' EP, ''From Eden'' EP and ''Hozier''===\n{{Main|Hozier (album)}}\n[[File:Hozier at Lollapalooza.jpg|thumb|left|Hozier performing at Lollapalooza, Chicago in January 2014]]\nIn July 2013, Hozier released the [[extended play|EP]] ''Take Me to Church''. The title track was a blues-gospel pop song with lyrics about finding solace in a lover, and its video was directed by [[Brendan Canty]] and depicts [[LGBT rights in Russia|anti-gay violence in Russia]].<ref name= searing/><ref name= adored>Byrne, Niall (23 March 2014). \"He wants to be adored: The Wicklow singer Andrew Hozier-Byrne refuses to go down as a one-hit wonder, writes Niall Byrne in Austin\". ''Sunday Times'' (London). p. 22.</ref> Released in September, the video was shared by [[Stephen Fry]], appeared on the front page of [[Reddit]], and went viral.<ref name= propelling/><ref>Flanagan, Andrew (7 October 2013). \"[http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/5748114/birth-of-a-buzz-behind-the-scenes-as-hozier-goes-viral Birth of a Buzz: Behind the Scenes as Hozier Goes Viral]\". ''Billboard''. Retrieved 3 June 2014.</ref><ref name= searing>Mullally, Una (12 October 2013). \"Hozier's soaring voice and searing heart: From quiet beginnings, the 'Take Me to Church' singer's music, and its political nous, are growing in depth and stature\". ''Irish Times'' (Dublin).</ref> The single achieved global success, scoring top five positions around the world and gaining multi-platinum certifications.\n\nIn 2014, Hozier released his second EP, ''From Eden''. One of the tracks, \"Cherry Wine\", appeared in [[Zach Braff]]'s movie \"[[Wish I Was Here]]\", chosen for its \"heartbreaking lyrics and poetry\".<ref>Ward, James (12 July 2014). \"Hozier hits right note in Zach Braff's new movie\". ''The Daily Mirror'' (London). p. 27.</ref> It was later performed on the [[The Late Late Show (Irish talk show)|Late Late Show (Irish Talk Show)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0pYY7rHvvDo|title=Hozier - Cherry Wine - The Late Late Show - RT\u00c9 One|last=The Late Late Show|date=11 March 2016|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/music-news/watch-hozier-performs-cherry-wine-on-the-late-late-show-with-james-corden-34604716.html|title=WATCH: Hozier performs Cherry Wine on The Late Late Show with James Corden |website=Independent.ie}}</ref>\n\nHozier released his self-titled album, ''[[Hozier (album)|Hozier]]'', in September 2014. It featured five singles, including \"Take Me to Church\", \"[[Someone New (Hozier song)|Someone New]]\", \"[[Work Song (Hozier song)|Work Song]]\", and \"[[From Eden]]\". He embarked on an American and a European tour to support the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pacificsandiego.com/things-to-do/music/pac-hozier-announces-new-fall-concert-dates-story.html|title=Hozier announces new fall concert dates|last=Varga|first=George|date=20 April 2015|website=|publisher=Pacific Sandiego|accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"Take Me to Church\" was later nominated at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] in 2015. At the awards show, he performed the song with [[Annie Lennox]],<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/hozier-annie-lennox-duet-grammy-awards/| website= Evoke.ie| title= Superstar duet! Guess who Hozier is performing with at the Grammy Awards?| date= 29 January 2015| access-date= 9 February 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170630182306/http://evoke.ie/showbiz/hozier-annie-lennox-duet-grammy-awards| archive-date= 30 June 2017| url-status= dead}}</ref> and later at the [[2015 Billboard Music Awards|2015 ''Billboard'' Music Awards]]. On 12 November 2015, he won the [[VH1]] Artist of the Year, based on fan votes. He also performed \"Take Me to Church\" and [[The Beatles]]' \"Blackbird\" with singer [[Tori Kelly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/223025/hozier-tori-kelly-blackbird-you-oughta-know-big-music/|title=We Need More Hozier + Tori Kelly Collabs Like This Joint Performance Of \"Blackbird\" At VH1's Big Music In 2015 Concert|website=Vh1.com}}</ref> In June 2016, Hozier released the song \"Better Love\" as part of the ''[[The Legend of Tarzan (film)|Legend of Tarzan]]'' soundtrack.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.facebook.com/hoziermusic/videos/1017072688346065/ | title= Hozier announced the song \"Better Love\"|publisher=[[Facebook]]| date= 15 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wm4CrOfbHMI | title= Hozier - Better Love (From The Legend of Tarzan - Single Version)|publisher=[[YouTube]] | date= 16 June 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Hozier at the Troubadour in West Hollywood (14238011522).jpg|thumb|Hozier performing at the Troubadour in West Hollywood.]]\n\n=== 2018\u2013present: ''Nina Cried Power'' EP and ''Wasteland, Baby!'' ===\n{{main|Nina Cried Power|Wasteland, Baby!}}\nIn September 2018, Hozier returned with the release of the EP ''[[Nina Cried Power]]''. The record features a collaboration with [[Mavis Staples]] on the title track, as well as three other songs, titled \"NFWMB\", \"Moment's Silence (Common Tongue)\", and \"Shrike\". The singer then stated that he was recording his second studio album. The title track, \"Nina Cried Power\" opposes xenophobia<ref name=\":0\" /> and references various musicians, acknowledging their contributions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/15332146/Hozier-nina-cried-power/Patti-cried-power|title=Patti cried power|website=Genius|language=en|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nHozier's second album, ''[[Wasteland, Baby!]]'', was released on 1 March 2019, debuting atop the US [[Billboard 200]] chart.<ref> {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8500815/hozier-wasteland-baby-interview|title= Hozier Knows the World Is Ending, So He Wrote Apocalyptic Love Songs For 'Wasteland, Baby!'|publisher=Billboard|last=Hughes|first=Hilary|accessdate=10 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/columns/chart-beat/8501829/hozier-debuts-no-1-billboard-200-chart-wasteland-baby|title=Hozier Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart With 'Wasteland, Baby!'|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=11 March 2019}}</ref> The album's cover was painted by Hozier's mother who also created the artwork covers for some of his previous releases.<ref>{{Citation|last=Hozier|title=Hozier - Wasteland, Baby! - Behind The Album Cover|date=2019-02-28|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k-ISqUzOqJo|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> He embarked on a worldwide tour, visiting venues across North America, Australia, New Zealand, and Europe, beginning on 10 March 2019 to support the album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hozier Adds Fall Dates to North American Tour|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/live/8501891/hozier-fall-dates-north-american-tour|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=He'll take you to church: Hozier announces UK and European tour for 2019|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/hozier-announces-uk-european-tour-2019-2447302/amp|publisher=NME|accessdate=13 March 2019|date=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe released the album\u2019s lead single, \"Movement\", on 14 November 2018 along with the music video which featured [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] [[Ballet]] dancer [[Sergei Polunin]]. Polunin had previously performed on Hozier's \"Take Me to Church\" video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/hozier-new-single-movement-album-release-tour-music-video-sergei-polunin-a8634586.html|title=Hozier teams up with baller dancer Sergei Polunin in 'Movement' music video|date=2018-11-15|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8484970/hozier-movement-song-video-ballet-dancer-sergei-polunin-watch|title=Hozier Premieres Passionate 'Movement' Video Starring Ballet Dancer Sergei Polunin: Watch|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref> Subsequently, he also released \"Almost (Sweet Music)\" on 16 January 2019 and \"Dinner and Diatribes\" on 15 February 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Acevedo |first=Angelica |title=Hozier Announces 'Wasteland, Baby!' Release Date, Debuts New Song 'Almost (Sweet Music)' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8493800/hozier-announces-wasteland-baby-release-date |accessdate=10 February 2019 |work=Billboard |date=16 January 2019}}</ref> He released the music video for \"Dinner and Diatribes\" on 6 March 2019, featuring [[Anya Taylor-Joy]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radio.com/blogs/tiana-timmerberg/hozier-becomes-your-worst-nightmare-eerie-dinner-diatribes-music-video|title=Hozier Becomes Your Worst Nightmare in Eerie 'Dinner & Diatribes' Music Video|date=2019-03-06|website=www.radio.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> and directed by Anthony Byrne who also directed the video for \"Someone New\". Two songs from the ''Nina Cried Power'' EP, the title track and \"Shrike\", are also included on the album.<ref>{{cite news |last=Skinner |first=Tom |title=Hozier has announced 'Wasteland, Baby' \u2013 his first album in more than four years |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/hozier-new-album-wasteland-baby-single2431741-2431741 |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=NME |date=16 January 2019}}</ref> The song \"No Plan\" is greatly influenced by a lecture delivered by astrophysicist [[Katie Mack (astrophysicist)|Katie Mack]]<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AstroKatie/status/1101392520393752576|title=Especially this track \"No Plan\"\u2026 trust me on this|last=Mack|first=Katie|date=2019-03-01|via=Twitter|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> about the end of the universe.\n\nHe was the closing headliner of the inaugural Railbird Festival held on the grounds of the [[Keeneland]] horse track in [[Lexington,_Kentucky|Lexington, Kentucky]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.visitlex.com/media/press-releases/post/railbird-festival-reveals-inaugural-artist-lineup-ticket-levels-and-premium-experiences/ |title = Railbird Festival Reveals Inaugural Artist Lineup, Ticket Levels and Premium Experiences|date = 26 March 2019}}</ref> He was one of the headliners for the [[Electric Picnic]] 2019, a three-day festival held in Ireland on 30 August to 1 September.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/hozier-the-strokes-the-1975-and-florence-the-machine-to-headline-electric-picnic-2019-2461128|title=Hozier, The Strokes, The 1975 and Florence & The Machine to headline Electric Picnic 2019|last=Reilly|first=Nick|date=2019-03-13|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref> He performed at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] 2019, a five-day festival held in June in England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/festivals/8502658/glastonbury-2019-headliners-killers-the-cure-stormzy-miley-cyrus-janet-jackson|title=Glastonbury 2019 Headliners Include Killers, The Cure, Stormzy, Miley Cyrus, Janet Jackson|accessdate=21 March 2019|publisher=Billboard}}</ref> He also performed at the [[Lollapalooza]] 2019, a four-day music festival held in Chicago in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/festivals/8503287/2019-lollapalooza-lineup-see-full-list|title=Ariana Grande, Childish Gambino, Twenty One Pilots, The Strokes Headlining 2019 Lollapalooza: Full Lineup|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March and April 2020, he did multiple live-streamed performances on Instagram and Facebook to raise money and awareness for the [[Irish Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children|Irish Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children (ISPCC)]] during the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|2020 Coronavirus pandemic.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nialler9.com/irish-artists-hozier-dermot-kennedy-kodaline-more-to-live-stream-charity-gigs-with-ispcc-childline-rte-2fm/|title=Irish artists Hozier, Dermot Kennedy, Kodaline & more to live stream charity gigs with ISPCC/Childline & RT\u00c9 2FM|last=Nialler9|website=Nialler9|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> On 27 March, he performed on the Late Late Show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/news/hozier-parting-glass-covid19|title=WATCH: Hozier performs chilling rendition of Parting Glass|date=2020-03-28|website=IrishCentral.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> On 14 April, he announced that he was releasing his cover of [[The Parting Glass|\u201cThe Parting Glass\u201d]] for streaming on all platforms, with proceeds going to ISPCC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-9DIBnpIaR/|title=Andrew Hozier Byrne on Instagram: \u201cHappy to announce the performance of the Parting Glass from @latelaterte will be out this Friday on all platforms with all proceeds going\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Social messages in songs ==\nThe \"[[Take Me to Church]]\" music video features two men in a same sex relationship, and highlights the injustices and violence perpetrated against members of the [[LGBT]] community. The video was inspired by videos of violent crimes against gay men in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/music/hozier-ditches-church-gets-political-on-new-ep-10884076|title=Hozier Ditches 'Church,' Gets Political on New EP|last=Cabral|first=Angelica|date=2018-10-11|website=Phoenix New Times|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref> \n\nThe music video for the song \"[[Cherry Wine (Hozier song)|Cherry Wine]]\" was released to raise awareness of domestic violence.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SdSCCwtNEjA | title= Hozier- Cherry Wine| date= 13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Nina Cried Power]]\" is a song that highlights artists such as [[Nina Simone]], [[Bob Dylan]], and [[Mavis Staples]] whose work takes a political or social justice stance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/music/hozier-ditches-church-gets-political-on-new-ep-10884076|title=Hozier Ditches 'Church,' Gets Political on New EP|last=Cabral|first=Angelica|date=2018-10-11|website=Phoenix New Times|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref> The song itself has been said to be a \"thank you to the spirit and legacy of protest.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hozier.com/ninacriedpowercast/|title=Activists featured in the Nina Cried Power video|last=www.hozier.com|first=Hozier-|website=Hozier|language=en|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref> The music video features Irish activists alongside protest footage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/entertainment/hoziers-nina-cried-power-video-is-a-tribute-to-irish-activists-868801.html|title=Hozier's Nina Cried Power video is a tribute to Irish activists|last=Thursday|last2=September 13|date=2018-09-13|website=www.irishexaminer.com|access-date=2019-03-26|last3=Pm|first3=2018-02:18}}</ref>\n\n\"Be\" also contains many allusions to [[sea level rise]] and refugee crises. Hozier sings: \"When the man who gives the order, Is born next time around on the boat sent back, When the bodies starving at the border, Are on TV givin' people the sack, Oh, when the sea rises to meet us\". This is also a reference to US President [[Donald Trump]], who prior to his presidential campaign was well known for firing people on his reality TV show ''[[The Apprentice (US)|The Apprentice]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/16612538|title=Genius lyrics - Hozier, Be - 'Are on TV givin' people the sack'|last=bluejaysjay|first=genuis lyrics|date=2019-03-01|website=Genius Lyrics|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Hozier released a new song entitled \"Jackboot Jump\", following live performances of it on tour. This song, besides being a direct reference to George Orwell's ''1984'' alludes to social demonstrations in Hong Kong, Russia and in America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/hozier-shared-new-live-song-jackboot-jump-listen-now-2577396|title=Listen to Hozier's politically charged new live song 'Jackboot Jump' {{!}} NME|date=2019-11-22|website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nAlluding to upcoming songs, Hozier also performed a new song whilst on tour entitled \"But the Wages\" that refers to temperatures rising as well as riots all around the world, while wages remain the same.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=jPTrurPsBms|title=But The Wages|last=Hozier|first=|date=|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:17em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions<!--Recommended limit is 10-->\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\"| Sales\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br/><ref name=\"IRE\">{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Hozier|title=Discography Hozier|publisher=Irish Charts Portal. Hung Medien}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br/><ref name=\"AUS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Hozier&titel=Hozier&cat=a|title=Discography Hozier|publisher=Australian Charts Portal. Hung Medien}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br>(FL)]]<br/><ref name=\"FL\">{{cite web|