{"title_page": "Being There", "text_new": "{{about|the film|the novel|Being There (novel)|other uses}}\n{{redirect|Chauncey Gardner|the American Football player|Chauncey Gardner-Johnson}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Being There\n| image          = Original movie poster for Being There.jpg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Hal Ashby]]\n| producer       = Andrew Braunsberg\n| screenplay     = [[Jerzy Kosi\u0144ski]]{{Efn|name=fn1|[[Robert C. Jones]] worked extensively on the screenplay. He has said that both he and Kosi\u0144ski initially shared a writing credit, but the [[Writers Guild of America]] overruled the decision and awarded Kosi\u0144ski sole credit.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://cinemontage.org/2014/03/robert-c-jones-2014-ace-career-achievement-award-honoree/|website = Cinemontage|publisher = [[Motion Picture Editors Guild]]|date = March 1, 2014|accessdate = November 22, 2018|last = Kaufman|first = Debra|title = Robert C. Jones: 2014 ACE Career Achievement Award Honoree}}</ref>}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Being There (novel)|Being There]]''|Jerzy Kosi\u0144ski}}\n| starring       = [[Peter Sellers]]<br />[[Shirley MacLaine]]<br />[[Jack Warden]]<br />[[Melvyn Douglas]]<br />[[Richard Dysart]]<br />[[Richard Basehart]]\n| music          = [[Johnny Mandel]]\n| cinematography = [[Caleb Deschanel]]\n| editing        = [[Don Zimmerman (film editor)|Don Zimmerman]]\n| studio         = [[Lorimar Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1979|12|19}}\n| runtime        = 130 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $7 million<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=DSCfnVzRUGYC&pg=PA176&q=shampoo%201975%20budget \"The Films of Hal Ashby\".] Beach, Christopher (2009). Detroit, Michigan: [[Wayne State University Press]], p. 177, {{ISBN|978-0-8143-3415-7}}.</ref>\n| gross          = $30.2 million (US)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=beingthere.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|title=Being There, Box Office Information|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Being There''''' is a 1979 American [[Comedy-drama|comedy-drama film]] directed by [[Hal Ashby]]. Based on the [[Being There (novel)|1970 novel of the same name]] by [[Jerzy Kosi\u0144ski]], it was [[film adaptation|adapted]] for the screen by Kosi\u0144ski and the uncredited [[Robert C. Jones]]. The film stars [[Peter Sellers]] and [[Shirley MacLaine]], and features [[Jack Warden]], [[Melvyn Douglas]], [[Richard Dysart]], and [[Richard Basehart]].\n\nDouglas won the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] and Sellers was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1980|title=The 52nd Academy Awards (1980) Nominees and Winners|publisher=SAMPAS}}</ref> The screenplay won the [[British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Award]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] and the [[Writers Guild of America Award]] for [[Writers Guild of America Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Comedy Adapted from Another Medium]]. It was also nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]].\n\nIn 2015, the United States [[Library of Congress]] selected ''Being There'' for preservation in the [[National Film Registry]], finding it \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ghostbusters-top-gun-enter-national-849092|title='Ghostbusters,' 'Top Gun,' 'Shawshank' Enter National Film Registry|author=Mike Barnes|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nMiddle-aged, simple-minded Chance lives in the townhouse of a wealthy old man in [[Washington, D.C.]]. He has spent his whole life tending the garden and has never left the property. Other than gardening, his knowledge is derived entirely from what he sees on television. When his benefactor dies, Chance naively tells the lawyers that he has no claim against the estate and is ordered to move out.\n\nChance wanders aimlessly, discovering the outside world for the first time. Passing by a TV shop, he sees himself captured by a camera in the shop window. Entranced, he steps backward off the sidewalk and is struck by a chauffeured car owned by elderly business mogul Ben Rand. In the car is Rand's much younger wife Eve, who mishears \"Chance, the gardener\" in reply to the question who he is, as \"Chauncey Gardiner.\"\n\nEve brings Chance to their home to recover. He is wearing expensive tailored clothes from the 1920s and 1930s, which his benefactor had allowed him to take from the attic, and his manners are old-fashioned and courtly. When Ben Rand meets him, he takes \"Chauncey\" for an upper-class, highly-educated businessman who has fallen on hard times. Rand admires him, finding him direct, wise and insightful.\n\nRand is also a confidant and advisor to the [[President of the United States]], whom he introduces to \"Chauncey.\" In a discussion about the economy, Chance takes his cue from the words \"stimulate growth\" and talks about the changing seasons of the garden. The President misinterprets this as optimistic political advice and quotes \u201cChauncey Gardiner\u201d in a speech. Chance now rises to national prominence, attends important dinners, develops a close connection with the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] ambassador, and appears on a television talk show during which his detailed advice about what a serious gardener should do is misunderstood as his opinion on what would be his presidential policy.\n\nThough he has now risen to the top of Washington society, the [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] and some 16 other agencies are unable to find any background information on him. During this time Rand's physician, Dr. Allenby, becomes increasingly suspicious that Chance is not a wise political expert and that the mystery of his identity may have a more mundane explanation. Dr. Allenby considers telling Rand this, but realizing how happy Chance is making him in his final days keeps him silent. \n\nThe dying Rand encourages Eve to become close to \"Chauncey.\" She is already attracted to him and makes a sexual advance. Chance has no interest in or knowledge of sex, but mimics a kissing scene from the 1968 film ''[[The Thomas Crown Affair (1968 film)|The Thomas Crown Affair]]'', which happens to be showing on the TV. When the scene ends, Chauncey stops suddenly and Eve is confused. She asks what he likes, meaning sexually; he replies \"I like to watch,\" meaning television. She is momentarily taken aback, but decides she is willing to [[masturbate]] for his voyeuristic pleasure, thereby not noticing that he has turned back to the TV and is now imitating a yoga exercise on a different channel.\n\nChance is present at Rand's death and shows genuine sadness at his passing. Questioned by Dr. Allenby, he admits that he \"loves Eve very much\" and also that he is just a gardener. When he leaves to inform Eve of Ben's death, Allenby says to himself, \"I understand,\" but interpretation of that is left to the viewer. \n\nWhile the President delivers a speech at Rand's funeral, the pallbearers hold a whispered discussion over potential replacements for the President in the next term of office and unanimously agree on Chauncey Gardiner as successor. Oblivious to all this, Chance wanders off through Rand's wintry estate. He straightens out a pine [[Tree#Overview|sapling]] flattened by a fallen branch, then walks across the surface of a lake. He pauses, dips his umbrella deep into the water under his feet, then continues on, while the President is heard quoting Rand: \"Life is a state of mind.\"\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* [[Peter Sellers]] as Chance the gardener (Chauncey Gardiner)\n* [[Shirley MacLaine]] as Eve Rand\n* [[Melvyn Douglas]] as Ben Rand\n* [[Richard A. Dysart]] as Dr. Robert Allenby\n* [[Jack Warden]] as the President\n* [[Richard Basehart]] as Soviet Ambassador Vladimir Skrapinov\n* [[Than Wyenn]] as Ambassador Gaufridi\n* [[David Clennon]] as Thomas Franklin\n* [[Fran Brill]] as Sally Hayes\n* [[Ruth Attaway]] as Louise\n* [[Denise DuBarry]] as Johanna\n* [[Sam Weisman]] as Colson\n* [[Alice Hirson]] as the First Lady\n* Arthur Rosenberg as Morton Hull\n* [[Jerome Hellman]] as Gary Burns\n* [[James Noble (actor)|James Noble]] as Kaufman\n* [[John Harkins (actor)|John Harkins]] as Courtney\n* [[Elya Baskin]] as Karpatov\n* [[Richard McKenzie (actor)|Richard McKenzie]] as Ron Steigler\n* [[Oteil Burbridge]] as Lolo (boy on corner)\n* Hoyt Clark Harris, Jr. as Secret Service agent Riff\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Filming==\nPrincipal filming occurred at the [[Biltmore Estate]], the largest private home in America, located in [[Asheville, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Henion|first=Leigh Ann|title=A Behind-the-Scenes Visit to Biltmore|date=March 2011|work=[[Our State]]|url=http://www.ourstate.com/biltmore-insiders-tour/|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMelvyn Douglas's granddaughter, [[Illeana Douglas]], visited the set and met Peter Sellers, who is her favorite actor. She has since credited the film for inspiring her to pursue a career in acting. According to Illeana, Sellers and Douglas had known each other since the 1940s, when they first met in [[Burma]] during [[World War II]]. They often reminisced about their war days while on the set.<ref name=francisco>{{cite web|last=Vigil|first=Delfin|title=Illeana Douglas inspired by Melvyn's 'Being There'|date=February 15, 2009|work=[[San Francisco Gate]]|url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Illeana-Douglas-inspired-by-Melvyn-s-Being-There-3250931.php#photo-2399605|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Burt Lancaster]] was Ashby's first choice for the role of Ben Rand.<ref name=sikov>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rZGZAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT439&dq=burt+lancaster+laurence+olivier+being+there+masturbation&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiL3rGszavjAhVbLs0KHX4uD-gQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=burt%20lancaster%20laurence%20olivier%20being%20there%20masturbation&f=false|last=Sikov|first=Ed|title=Mr. Strangelove: A Biography of Peter Sellers|year=2003|publisher=Hachette Books|isbn=9781401398941}}{{page needed|date=July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ayGlICMwYD0C&pg=PA226&q=being%20there%20outtake%20oscar#v=onepage&q=burt%20lancaster&f=false|last=Dawson|first=Nick|title=Being Hal Ashby: Life of a Hollywood Rebel|year=2009|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=9780813139197}}page 210</ref>  [[Laurence Olivier]] was also considered for the role, but he turned it down because of the masturbation scene.<ref name=sikov/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1SqXAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA30&q=laurence%20olivier%20being%20there%20ben%20rand|last=Mell|first=Eila|title=Casting Might-Have-Beens: A Film by Film Directory of Actors Considered for Roles Given to Others|year=2005|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9781476609768}}page 30</ref>\n\nAccording to MacLaine, \"(Peter) believed he was Chauncey. He never had lunch with me... He was Chauncey Gardiner the whole shoot, but believing he was having a love affair with me.\"<ref>\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EkdXTaHsSu0 Shirley MacLaine On What Peter Sellers Was Really Like]\" on [[YouTube]]</ref>\n\nThe making of the film is portrayed in ''[[The Life and Death of Peter Sellers]]'', a biographical film of Sellers' life.\n\n==Music==\nIncidental music is used very sparingly. What little original music is used was composed by [[Johnny Mandel]], and primarily features two recurrent piano themes based on \"[[Gnossiennes|Gnossienne]]s\" No. 4 and No. 6 by [[Erik Satie]]. The other major piece of music used is the [[Eumir Deodato]] jazz/funk arrangement of the opening fanfare from ''[[Also sprach Zarathustra (Strauss)|Also Sprach Zarathustra]]'' by [[Richard Strauss]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Vi3vz7qbtwC&pg=PA9&q=also%20sprach%20zarathustra%20being%20there|last=Stoehr|first=Ingo Roland|title=German Literature of the Twentieth Century: From Aestheticism to Postmodernism|year=2001|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=9781571131577}}</ref>\n\nMandel was also assisted by his late cousin and fellow composer [[Miles Goodman]] with the orchestration of the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Miles Goodman, 47, Composer for Films|date=August 20, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/20/arts/miles-goodman-47-composer-for-films.html|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jablon|first=Robert|title=MILES GOODMAN, FILM COMPOSER AND JAZZ RECORD PRODUCER, DIES|date=August 18, 1996|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1996/Miles-Goodman-Film-Composer-and-Jazz-Record-Producer-Dies/id-cdd69bf7e9fadd7e532dffd061c48a79|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Oliver|first=Myrna|title=Miles Goodman; Record Producer, Film Composer|date=August 20, 1996|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-08-20/local/me-35989_1_goodman-s-co-producer-reclusive-composer-miles-goodman|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Miles Goodman: Composer|date=August 22, 1996|work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19960822&id=wD8gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=C30EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2263,1662626|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Record producer, composer Miles Goodman dies at 47|date=August 21, 1996|work=[[The Daily Gazette]]|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1957&dat=19960821&id=-r9KAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hOkMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4020,4884243|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>http://screenprism.com/insights/article/why-does-being-there-highlight-basketball-jones-so-prominently</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe film opened to positive reviews, and gave Sellers a hit after many of his previous films outside of the ''Pink Panther'' series had flopped. Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] awarded a full grade of 4 out of 4 stars in his original print review<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/being-there-1980 |title=Being There |last=Ebert |first=Roger |authorlink=Roger Ebert |website=[[RogerEbert.com]] |accessdate=November 24, 2018 }}</ref> and mentions the final scene in his 2005 book ''The Great Movies II'' (p.&nbsp;52),<ref>{{citation | year=2006 | title = The Great Movies II | first=Roger | last=Ebert | authorlink = Roger Ebert | publisher=Random House, Inc. | isbn=978-0-7679-1986-9 | page=52 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sdv8LRB6a88C&pg=PA52}}</ref> stating that his film students once suggested that Chance may be walking on a submerged [[pier]]. Ebert writes, \"The movie presents us with an image, and while you may discuss the meaning of the image, it is not permitted to devise explanations for it. Since Ashby does not show a pier, there is no pier\u2014a movie is exactly what it shows us, and nothing more.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Being There review |first=Roger |last=Ebert |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19970525/REVIEWS08/401010303 |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=May 25, 1997 |accessdate=December 12, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623115834/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F19970525%2FREVIEWS08%2F401010303 |archivedate=June 23, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] also gave the film a perfect grade of 4 stars, calling it \"one of those rare films, a work of such electric comedy that you are more likely to watch it in amazement than to break down and laugh.\"<ref>[[Gene Siskel|Siskel, Gene]] (February 8, 1980). \"Sellers builds on perfection in 'Being There'\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 3, p. 3.</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called the film \"a stately, beautifully acted satire with a premise that's funny but fragile.\"\n<ref>{{cite journal |last=Maslin |first=Janet |date=December 20, 1979 |title=Film: Ashby-Kosinksi 'Being There' |url= |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=C20 }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it \"an unusually fine film\" that \"represents Peter Sellers' most smashing work since the mid-1960s.\"<ref>{{cite journal |date=December 19, 1979 |title=Being There |url= |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |page=19 }}</ref> [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it \"a gentle, exquisitely funny film,\" adding, \"Sellers hasn't been so terrific\u2014or had such terrific material\u2014in years.\"<ref>[[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Thomas, Kevin]] (December 20, 1979). \"A Kosinski Novel Comes to Life\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 36.</ref>\n\nVincent Misiano reviewed ''Being There'' in ''[[Ares (magazine)|Ares Magazine]]'' #3 and commented that \"The film's humor never flags and yet its delicately bitter irony is never far away. It satirizes politics and politicians, business and businessmen, and, finally, all the rest of us and what we imagine we see when we look at one another.\"<ref name=\"Ares\">{{cite journal | last=Misiano | first=Vincent | title=Film & Television | journal=[[Ares (magazine)|Ares Magazine]] | publisher=[[Simulations Publications, Inc.]] | date=July 1980 | issue=3 | page=32}}</ref>\n\nThe credits at the film's end roll over an [[outtake]], known as the \"Rafael outtake.\" Sellers was later displeased that the outtake ran because he believed it took away from Chauncey's mystique.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kim|first=Wook|title=After 'The End': 10 Memorable End-Credit Scenes|date=November 26, 2012|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2012/11/27/after-the-end-10-memorable-end-credit-scenes/slide/being-there/|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref> He also believed the outtake was what prevented him from winning the Oscar.<ref name=francisco/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ayGlICMwYD0C&pg=PA226&q=being%20there%20outtake%20oscar|last=Dawson|first=Nick|title=Being Hal Ashby: Life of a Hollywood Rebel|year=2009|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=9780813173344}}page 226</ref>\n\nAn alternative credit sequence has waves on a television set as they would appear on an \"unoccupied\" channel.\n\nThe film holds a score of 94% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 52 reviews, with an average grade of 8.6 out of 10. The critical consensus reads: \"Smart, sophisticated, and refreshingly subtle, ''Being There'' soars behind sensitive direction from Hal Ashby and a stellar Peter Sellers performance.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/being_there/ |title=Being There |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=November 24, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n[[Melvyn Douglas]] won his second [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] and [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Flint|first=Peter B.|title=MELVYN DOUGLAS DEAD; ACTOR, 80, WON 2 OSCARS|date=August 5, 1981|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/08/05/obituaries/melvyn-douglas-dead-actor-80-won-2-oscars.html|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Reid|first=Joe|title=The Oscar Ballot Explained: Best Supporting Actor/Actress|date=February 24, 2014|url=http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/02/oscar-ballot-explained-best-supporting-actoractress/358460/|publisher=[[Thewire.com]]|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[52nd Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| [[Peter Sellers]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Melvyn Douglas]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[34th British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Awards]]\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| Andrew Braunsberg\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]]\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress in a Leading Role]]\n| [[Shirley MacLaine]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n| [[Jerzy Kosi\u0144ski]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[1979 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]]\n| [[Palme d'Or]]\n| [[Hal Ashby]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Fotogramas de Plata Awards\n| Best Foreign Performer\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[37th Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]\n| ''Being There''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor in a Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress in a Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] \n| Shirley MacLaine\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor - Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]\n| Melvyn Douglas\n| {{won}}{{efn|Tied with [[Robert Duvall]] for ''[[Apocalypse Now]]''.}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director \u2013 Motion Picture]]\n| Hal Ashby\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay \u2013 Motion Picture]]\n| Jerzy Kosinski\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Japan Academy Film Prize]]\n| [[Japan Academy Prize for Outstanding Foreign Language Film|Outstanding Foreign Language Film]]\n| Hal Ashby\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[London Critics Circle Film Awards]]\n| Special Achievement Award\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards 1979|Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards]]\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| Melvyn Douglas <small>(also for ''[[The Seduction of Joe Tynan]]'')</small>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[National Board of Review Awards 1979|National Board of Review Awards]]\n| [[National Board of Review: Top Ten Films|Top Ten Films]]\n| ''Being There''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[National Board of Review Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[National Film Preservation Board]]\n| [[National Film Registry]]\n| ''Being There''\n| {{won|Inducted}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[National Society of Film Critics Awards 1979|National Society of Film Critics Awards]]\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| Melvyn Douglas\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n| Jerzy Kosinski and [[Robert C. Jones]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| [[Caleb Deschanel]] <small>(also for ''[[The Black Stallion (film)|The Black Stallion]]'')</small>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[1979 New York Film Critics Circle Awards|New York Film Critics Circle Awards]]\n| [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| Melvyn Douglas\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Jerzy Kosinski\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[32nd Writers Guild of America Awards|Writers Guild of America Awards]]\n| [[Writers Guild of America Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Comedy Adapted from Another Medium]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in:\n* 2000: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs]] \u2013 #26<ref>{{cite web|title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs100.pdf |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nA 30th Anniversary Edition was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] in February 2009.<ref name=francisco/> [[The Criterion Collection]] issued the film on DVD and Blu-ray in March 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Wilkins|first=Budd|title=Being There|date=29 March 2017|magazine=[[Slant Magazine]]|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/dvd/review/being-there-bd|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Career of Nicodemus Dyzma]]'' \u2013 a novel said to bear strong resemblance to ''Being There'' and thus a subject of controversy in 1982.\n* [[Politics in fiction]] \u2013 a list of other fictional stories in which politics similarly features as an important plot element.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book\n  | last = Beech\n  | first = Christopher\n  | year = 2009\n  | title = The Films of Hal Ashby\n  | location = Detroit\n  | publisher = Wayne State University Press\n  | isbn = 978-0-8143-3415-7\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  | last = Finkelstein\n  | first = Joanne\n  | title = The Art of Self Invention: Image and Identity in Popular Visual Culture\n  | url = http://www.ibtauris.com/display.asp?ISB=9781845113957\n  | location = London\n  | publisher = I. B. Tauris\n  | year = 2007\n  | pages = 9, 98\u201399\n  | isbn = 1-84511-395-0\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  | last = Nichols\n  | first = Peter M.\n  | author2 = A. O. Scott\n  | author3 = Vincent Canby\n  | year = 2004\n  | title = The New York Times Guide to the Best 1,000 Movies Ever Made\n  | location = New York\n  | publisher = Macmillan\n  | pages = 93\u201394\n  | isbn = 0-312-32611-4\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  | last = Sikov\n  | first = Ed\n  | title = Mr. Strangelove: A Biography of Peter Sellers\n  | location = New York\n  | publisher = Hyperion\n  | year = 2002\n  | isbn = 0-7868-8581-5\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  | last = Tichi\n  | first = Cecelia\n  | title = Electronic Hearth: Creating an American Television Culture\n  | location = New York\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | year = 1991\n  | isbn = 0-19-507914-0\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* Being There essay by Jerry Dean Roberts on the National Film Registry site.[https://www.loc.gov/static/programs/national-film-preservation-board/documents/BeingThere.pdf]\n*{{IMDb title|0078841}}\n* {{allrovi movie|4708}}\n* {{mojo title|beingthere}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|being_there}}\n*[https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/4473-being-there-american-cipher ''Being There: American Cipher''] an essay by [[Mark Harris (journalist)|Mark Harris]] at the [[Criterion Collection]]\n*  [https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2020/01/23/34-best-political-movies-ever-made/  [[Ann Hornaday]], \"The 34 best political movies ever made\" ''The Washington Post'' Jan. 23, 2020)], ranked #24\n\n{{Hal Ashby}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Film}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Being There}}\n[[Category:1979 films]]\n[[Category:1970s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American political satire films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about fictional Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Films about television]]\n[[Category:Films about the media]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Hal Ashby]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Musical or Comedy Actor Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Supporting Actor Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Johnny Mandel]]\n[[Category:Films set in country houses]]\n[[Category:Films set in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Films set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Films shot in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Screenplay BAFTA Award]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the film|the novel|Being There (novel)|other uses}}\n{{redirect|Chauncey Gardner|the American Football player|Chauncey Gardner-Johnson}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Being There\n| image          = Original movie poster for Being There.jpg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Hal Ashby]]\n| producer       = Andrew Braunsberg\n| screenplay     = [[Jerzy Kosi\u0144ski]]{{Efn|name=fn1|[[Robert C. Jones]] worked extensively on the screenplay. He has said that both he and Kosi\u0144ski initially shared a writing credit, but the [[Writers Guild of America]] overruled the decision and awarded Kosi\u0144ski sole credit.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://cinemontage.org/2014/03/robert-c-jones-2014-ace-career-achievement-award-honoree/|website = Cinemontage|publisher = [[Motion Picture Editors Guild]]|date = March 1, 2014|accessdate = November 22, 2018|last = Kaufman|first = Debra|title = Robert C. Jones: 2014 ACE Career Achievement Award Honoree}}</ref>}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Being There (novel)|Being There]]''|Jerzy Kosi\u0144ski}}\n| starring       = [[Peter Sellers]]<br />[[Shirley MacLaine]]<br />[[Jack Warden]]<br />[[Melvyn Douglas]]<br />[[Richard Dysart]]<br />[[Richard Basehart]]\n| music          = [[Johnny Mandel]]\n| cinematography = [[Caleb Deschanel]]\n| editing        = [[Don Zimmerman (film editor)|Don Zimmerman]]\n| studio         = [[Lorimar Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1979|12|19}}\n| runtime        = 130 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $7 million<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=DSCfnVzRUGYC&pg=PA176&q=shampoo%201975%20budget \"The Films of Hal Ashby\".] Beach, Christopher (2009). Detroit, Michigan: [[Wayne State University Press]], p. 177, {{ISBN|978-0-8143-3415-7}}.</ref>\n| gross          = $30.2 million (US)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=beingthere.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|title=Being There, Box Office Information|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Being There''''' is a 1979 American [[Comedy-drama|comedy-drama film]] directed by [[Hal Ashby]]. Based on the [[Being There (novel)|1970 novel of the same name]] by [[Jerzy Kosi\u0144ski]], it was [[film adaptation|adapted]] for the screen by Kosi\u0144ski and the uncredited [[Robert C. Jones]]. The film stars [[Peter Sellers]] and [[Shirley MacLaine]], and features [[Jack Warden]], [[Melvyn Douglas]], [[Richard Dysart]], and [[Richard Basehart]].\n\nDouglas won the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] and Sellers was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1980|title=The 52nd Academy Awards (1980) Nominees and Winners|publisher=SAMPAS}}</ref> The screenplay won the [[British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Award]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] and the [[Writers Guild of America Award]] for [[Writers Guild of America Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Comedy Adapted from Another Medium]]. It was also nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]].\n\nIn 2015, the United States [[Library of Congress]] selected ''Being There'' for preservation in the [[National Film Registry]], finding it \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ghostbusters-top-gun-enter-national-849092|title='Ghostbusters,' 'Top Gun,' 'Shawshank' Enter National Film Registry|author=Mike Barnes|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nMiddle-aged, simple-minded Chance lives in the townhouse of a wealthy old man in [[Washington, D.C.]]. He has spent his whole life tending the garden and has never left the property. Other than gardening, his knowledge is derived entirely from what he sees on television. When his benefactor dies, Chance naively tells the lawyers that he has no claim against the estate and is ordered to move out.\n\nChance wanders aimlessly, discovering the outside world for the first time. Passing by a TV shop, he sees himself captured by a camera in the shop window. Entranced, he steps backward off the sidewalk and is struck by a chauffeured car owned by elderly business mogul Ben Rand. In the car is Rand's much younger wife Eve, who mishears \"Chance, the gardener\" in reply to the question who he is, as \"Chauncey Gardiner.\"\n\nEve brings Chance to their home to recover. He is wearing expensive tailored clothes from the 1920s and 1930s, which his benefactor had allowed him to take from the attic, and his manners are old-fashioned and courtly. When Ben Rand meets him, he takes \"Chauncey\" for an upper-class, highly-educated businessman who has fallen on hard times. Rand admires him, finding him direct, wise and insightful.\n\nRand is also a confidant and advisor to the [[President of the United States]], whom he introduces to \"Chauncey.\" In a discussion about the economy, Chance takes his cue from the words \"stimulate growth\" and talks about the changing seasons of the garden. The President misinterprets this as optimistic political advice and quotes \u201cChauncey Gardiner\u201d in a speech. Chance now rises to national prominence, attends important dinners, develops a close connection with the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] ambassador, and appears on a television talk show during which his detailed advice about what a serious gardener should do is misunderstood as his opinion on what would be his presidential policy.\n\nThough he has now risen to the top of Washington society, the [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] and some 16 other agencies are unable to find any background information on him. During this time Rand's physician, Dr. Allenby, becomes increasingly suspicious that Chance is not a wise political expert and that the mystery of his identity may have a more mundane explanation. Dr. Allenby considers telling Rand this, but realizing how happy Chance is making him in his final days keeps him silent. \n\nThe dying Rand encourages Eve to become close to \"Chauncey.\" She is already attracted to him and makes a sexual advance. Chance has no interest in or knowledge of sex, but mimics a kissing scene from the 1968 film ''[[The Thomas Crown Affair (1968 film)|The Thomas Crown Affair]]'', which happens to be showing on the TV. When the scene ends, Chauncey stops suddenly and Eve is confused. She asks what he likes, meaning sexually; he replies \"I like to watch,\" meaning television. She is momentarily taken aback, but decides she is willing to [[masturbate]] for his voyeuristic pleasure, thereby not noticing that he has turned back to the TV and is now imitating a yoga exercise on a different channel.\n\nChance is present at Rand's death and shows genuine sadness at his passing. Questioned by Dr. Allenby, he admits that he \"loves Eve very much\" and also that he is just a gardener. When he leaves to inform Eve of Ben's death, Allenby says to himself, \"I understand,\" but interpretation of that is left to the viewer. \n\nWhile the President delivers a speech at Rand's funeral, the pallbearers hold a whispered discussion over potential replacements for the President in the next term of office and unanimously agree on Chauncey Gardiner as successor. Oblivious to all this, Chance wanders off through Rand's wintry estate. He straightens out a pine [[Tree#Overview|sapling]] flattened by a fallen branch, then walks across the surface of a lake. He pauses, dips his umbrella deep into the water under his feet, then continues on, while the President is heard quoting Rand: \"Life is a state of mind.\"\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* [[Peter Sellers]] as Chance the gardener (Chauncey Gardiner)\n* [[Shirley MacLaine]] as Eve Rand\n* [[Melvyn Douglas]] as Ben Rand\n* [[Richard A. Dysart]] as Dr. Robert Allenby\n* [[Jack Warden]] as the President\n* [[Richard Basehart]] as Soviet Ambassador Vladimir Skrapinov\n* [[Than Wyenn]] as Ambassador Gaufridi\n* [[David Clennon]] as Thomas Franklin\n* [[Fran Brill]] as Sally Hayes\n* [[Ruth Attaway]] as Louise\n* [[Denise DuBarry]] as Johanna\n* [[Sam Weisman]] as Colson\n* [[Alice Hirson]] as the First Lady\n* Arthur Rosenberg as Morton Hull\n* [[Jerome Hellman]] as Gary Burns\n* [[James Noble (actor)|James Noble]] as Kaufman\n* [[John Harkins (actor)|John Harkins]] as Courtney\n* [[Elya Baskin]] as Karpatov\n* [[Richard McKenzie (actor)|Richard McKenzie]] as Ron Steigler\n* [[Oteil Burbridge]] as Lolo (boy on corner)\n* Hoyt Clark Harris, Jr. as Secret Service agent Riff\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Filming==\nPrincipal filming occurred at the [[Biltmore Estate]], the largest private home in America, located in [[Asheville, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Henion|first=Leigh Ann|title=A Behind-the-Scenes Visit to Biltmore|date=March 2011|work=[[Our State]]|url=http://www.ourstate.com/biltmore-insiders-tour/|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMelvyn Douglas's granddaughter, [[Illeana Douglas]], visited the set and met Peter Sellers, who is her favorite actor. She has since credited the film for inspiring her to pursue a career in acting. According to Illeana, Sellers and Douglas had known each other since the 1940s, when they first met in [[Burma]] during [[World War II]]. They often reminisced about their war days while on the set.<ref name=francisco>{{cite web|last=Vigil|first=Delfin|title=Illeana Douglas inspired by Melvyn's 'Being There'|date=February 15, 2009|work=[[San Francisco Gate]]|url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Illeana-Douglas-inspired-by-Melvyn-s-Being-There-3250931.php#photo-2399605|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Burt Lancaster]] was Ashby's first choice for the role of Ben Rand.<ref name=sikov>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rZGZAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT439&dq=burt+lancaster+laurence+olivier+being+there+masturbation&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiL3rGszavjAhVbLs0KHX4uD-gQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=burt%20lancaster%20laurence%20olivier%20being%20there%20masturbation&f=false|last=Sikov|first=Ed|title=Mr. Strangelove: A Biography of Peter Sellers|year=2003|publisher=Hachette Books|isbn=9781401398941}}{{page needed|date=July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ayGlICMwYD0C&pg=PA226&q=being%20there%20outtake%20oscar#v=onepage&q=burt%20lancaster&f=false|last=Dawson|first=Nick|title=Being Hal Ashby: Life of a Hollywood Rebel|year=2009|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=9780813139197}}page 210</ref>  [[Laurence Olivier]] was also considered for the role, but he turned it down because of the masturbation scene.<ref name=sikov/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1SqXAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA30&q=laurence%20olivier%20being%20there%20ben%20rand|last=Mell|first=Eila|title=Casting Might-Have-Beens: A Film by Film Directory of Actors Considered for Roles Given to Others|year=2005|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9781476609768}}page 30</ref>\n\nAccording to MacLaine, \"(Peter) believed he was Chauncey. He never had lunch with me... He was Chauncey Gardiner the whole shoot, but believing he was having a love affair with me.\"<ref>\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EkdXTaHsSu0 Shirley MacLaine On What Peter Sellers Was Really Like]\" on [[YouTube]]</ref>\n\nThe making of the film is portrayed in ''[[The Life and Death of Peter Sellers]]'', a biographical film of Sellers' life.\n\n==Music==\nIncidental music is used very sparingly. What little original music is used was composed by [[Johnny Mandel]], and primarily features two recurrent piano themes based on \"[[Gnossiennes|Gnossienne]]s\" No. 4 and No. 6 by [[Erik Satie]]. The other major piece of music used is the [[Eumir Deodato]] jazz/funk arrangement of the opening fanfare from ''[[Also sprach Zarathustra (Strauss)|Also Sprach Zarathustra]]'' by [[Richard Strauss]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Vi3vz7qbtwC&pg=PA9&q=also%20sprach%20zarathustra%20being%20there|last=Stoehr|first=Ingo Roland|title=German Literature of the Twentieth Century: From Aestheticism to Postmodernism|year=2001|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=9781571131577}}</ref>\n\nMandel was also assisted by his late cousin and fellow composer [[Miles Goodman]] with the orchestration of the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Miles Goodman, 47, Composer for Films|date=August 20, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/20/arts/miles-goodman-47-composer-for-films.html|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jablon|first=Robert|title=MILES GOODMAN, FILM COMPOSER AND JAZZ RECORD PRODUCER, DIES|date=August 18, 1996|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1996/Miles-Goodman-Film-Composer-and-Jazz-Record-Producer-Dies/id-cdd69bf7e9fadd7e532dffd061c48a79|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Oliver|first=Myrna|title=Miles Goodman; Record Producer, Film Composer|date=August 20, 1996|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-08-20/local/me-35989_1_goodman-s-co-producer-reclusive-composer-miles-goodman|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Miles Goodman: Composer|date=August 22, 1996|work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19960822&id=wD8gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=C30EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2263,1662626|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Record producer, composer Miles Goodman dies at 47|date=August 21, 1996|work=[[The Daily Gazette]]|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1957&dat=19960821&id=-r9KAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hOkMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4020,4884243|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>http://screenprism.com/insights/article/why-does-being-there-highlight-basketball-jones-so-prominently</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe film opened to positive reviews, and gave Sellers a hit after many of his previous films outside of the ''Pink Panther'' series had flopped. Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] awarded a full grade of 4 out of 4 stars in his original print review<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/being-there-1980 |title=Being There |last=Ebert |first=Roger |authorlink=Roger Ebert |website=[[RogerEbert.com]] |accessdate=November 24, 2018 }}</ref> and mentions the final scene in his 2005 book ''The Great Movies II'' (p.&nbsp;52),<ref>{{citation | year=2006 | title = The Great Movies II | first=Roger | last=Ebert | authorlink = Roger Ebert | publisher=Random House, Inc. | isbn=978-0-7679-1986-9 | page=52 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sdv8LRB6a88C&pg=PA52}}</ref> stating that his film students once suggested that Chance may be walking on a submerged [[pier]]. Ebert writes, \"The movie presents us with an image, and while you may discuss the meaning of the image, it is not permitted to devise explanations for it. Since Ashby does not show a pier, there is no pier\u2014a movie is exactly what it shows us, and nothing more.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Being There review |first=Roger |last=Ebert |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19970525/REVIEWS08/401010303 |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=May 25, 1997 |accessdate=December 12, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623115834/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F19970525%2FREVIEWS08%2F401010303 |archivedate=June 23, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] also gave the film a perfect grade of 4 stars, calling it \"one of those rare films, a work of such electric comedy that you are more likely to watch it in amazement than to break down and laugh.\"<ref>[[Gene Siskel|Siskel, Gene]] (February 8, 1980). \"Sellers builds on perfection in 'Being There'\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 3, p. 3.</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called the film \"a stately, beautifully acted satire with a premise that's funny but fragile.\"\n<ref>{{cite journal |last=Maslin |first=Janet |date=December 20, 1979 |title=Film: Ashby-Kosinksi 'Being There' |url= |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=C20 }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it \"an unusually fine film\" that \"represents Peter Sellers' most smashing work since the mid-1960s.\"<ref>{{cite journal |date=December 19, 1979 |title=Being There |url= |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |page=19 }}</ref> [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it \"a gentle, exquisitely funny film,\" adding, \"Sellers hasn't been so terrific\u2014or had such terrific material\u2014in years.\"<ref>[[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Thomas, Kevin]] (December 20, 1979). \"A Kosinski Novel Comes to Life\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 36.</ref>\n\nVincent Misiano reviewed ''Being There'' in ''[[Ares (magazine)|Ares Magazine]]'' #3 and commented that \"The film's humor never flags and yet its delicately bitter irony is never far away. It satirizes politics and politicians, business and businessmen, and, finally, all the rest of us and what we imagine we see when we look at one another.\"<ref name=\"Ares\">{{cite journal | last=Misiano | first=Vincent | title=Film & Television | journal=[[Ares (magazine)|Ares Magazine]] | publisher=[[Simulations Publications, Inc.]] | date=July 1980 | issue=3 | page=32}}</ref>\n\nThe credits at the film's end roll over an [[outtake]], known as the \"Rafael outtake.\" Sellers was later displeased that the outtake ran because he believed it took away from Chauncey's mystique.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kim|first=Wook|title=After 'The End': 10 Memorable End-Credit Scenes|date=November 26, 2012|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2012/11/27/after-the-end-10-memorable-end-credit-scenes/slide/being-there/|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref> He also believed the outtake was what prevented him from winning the Oscar.<ref name=francisco/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ayGlICMwYD0C&pg=PA226&q=being%20there%20outtake%20oscar|last=Dawson|first=Nick|title=Being Hal Ashby: Life of a Hollywood Rebel|year=2009|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=9780813173344}}page 226</ref>\n\nAn alternative credit sequence has waves on a television set as they would appear on an \"unoccupied\" channel.\n\nThe film holds a score of 94% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 52 reviews, with an average grade of 8.6 out of 10. The critical consensus reads: \"Smart, sophisticated, and refreshingly subtle, ''Being There'' soars behind sensitive direction from Hal Ashby and a stellar Peter Sellers performance.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/being_there/ |title=Being There |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=November 24, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n[[Melvyn Douglas]] won his second [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] and [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Flint|first=Peter B.|title=MELVYN DOUGLAS DEAD; ACTOR, 80, WON 2 OSCARS|date=August 5, 1981|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/08/05/obituaries/melvyn-douglas-dead-actor-80-won-2-oscars.html|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Reid|first=Joe|title=The Oscar Ballot Explained: Best Supporting Actor/Actress|date=February 24, 2014|url=http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/02/oscar-ballot-explained-best-supporting-actoractress/358460/|publisher=[[Thewire.com]]|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[52nd Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| [[Peter Sellers]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Melvyn Douglas]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[34th British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Awards]]\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| Andrew Braunsberg\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]]\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress in a Leading Role]]\n| [[Shirley MacLaine]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n| [[Jerzy Kosi\u0144ski]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[1979 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]]\n| [[Palme d'Or]]\n| [[Hal Ashby]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Fotogramas de Plata Awards\n| Best Foreign Performer\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[37th Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]\n| ''Being There''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor in a Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress in a Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] \n| Shirley MacLaine\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor - Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]\n| Melvyn Douglas\n| {{won}}{{efn|Tied with [[Robert Duvall]] for ''[[Apocalypse Now]]''.}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director \u2013 Motion Picture]]\n| Hal Ashby\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay \u2013 Motion Picture]]\n| Jerzy Kosinski\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Japan Academy Film Prize]]\n| [[Japan Academy Prize for Outstanding Foreign Language Film|Outstanding Foreign Language Film]]\n| Hal Ashby\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[London Critics Circle Film Awards]]\n| Special Achievement Award\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards 1979|Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards]]\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| Melvyn Douglas <small>(also for ''[[The Seduction of Joe Tynan]]'')</small>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[National Board of Review Awards 1979|National Board of Review Awards]]\n| [[National Board of Review: Top Ten Films|Top Ten Films]]\n| ''Being There''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[National Board of Review Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[National Film Preservation Board]]\n| [[National Film Registry]]\n| ''Being There''\n| {{won|Inducted}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[National Society of Film Critics Awards 1979|National Society of Film Critics Awards]]\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| Melvyn Douglas\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n| Jerzy Kosinski and [[Robert C. Jones]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| [[Caleb Deschanel]] <small>(also for ''[[The Black Stallion (film)|The Black Stallion]]'')</small>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[1979 New York Film Critics Circle Awards|New York Film Critics Circle Awards]]\n| [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Peter Sellers\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| Melvyn Douglas\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Jerzy Kosinski\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[32nd Writers Guild of America Awards|Writers Guild of America Awards]]\n| [[Writers Guild of America Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Comedy Adapted from Another Medium]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in:\n* 2000: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs]] \u2013 #26<ref>{{cite web|title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs100.pdf |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nA 30th Anniversary Edition was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] in February 2009.<ref name=francisco/> [[The Criterion Collection]] issued the film on DVD and Blu-ray in March 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Wilkins|first=Budd|title=Being There|date=29 March 2017|magazine=[[Slant Magazine]]|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/dvd/review/being-there-bd|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Career of Nicodemus Dyzma]]'' \u2013 a novel said to bear strong resemblance to ''Being There'' and thus a subject of controversy in 1982.\n* [[Politics in fiction]] \u2013 a list of other fictional stories in which politics similarly features as an important plot element.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book\n  | last = Beech\n  | first = Christopher\n  | year = 2009\n  | title = The Films of Hal Ashby\n  | location = Detroit\n  | publisher = Wayne State University Press\n  | isbn = 978-0-8143-3415-7\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  | last = Finkelstein\n  | first = Joanne\n  | title = The Art of Self Invention: Image and Identity in Popular Visual Culture\n  | url = http://www.ibtauris.com/display.asp?ISB=9781845113957\n  | location = London\n  | publisher = I. B. Tauris\n  | year = 2007\n  | pages = 9, 98\u201399\n  | isbn = 1-84511-395-0\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  | last = Nichols\n  | first = Peter M.\n  | author2 = A. O. Scott\n  | author3 = Vincent Canby\n  | year = 2004\n  | title = The New York Times Guide to the Best 1,000 Movies Ever Made\n  | location = New York\n  | publisher = Macmillan\n  | pages = 93\u201394\n  | isbn = 0-312-32611-4\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  | last = Sikov\n  | first = Ed\n  | title = Mr. Strangelove: A Biography of Peter Sellers\n  | location = New York\n  | publisher = Hyperion\n  | year = 2002\n  | isbn = 0-7868-8581-5\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  | last = Tichi\n  | first = Cecelia\n  | title = Electronic Hearth: Creating an American Television Culture\n  | location = New York\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | year = 1991\n  | isbn = 0-19-507914-0\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0078841}}\n* {{allrovi movie|4708}}\n* {{mojo title|beingthere}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|being_there}}\n*[https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/4473-being-there-american-cipher ''Being There: American Cipher''] an essay by [[Mark Harris (journalist)|Mark Harris]] at the [[Criterion Collection]]\n*  [https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2020/01/23/34-best-political-movies-ever-made/  [[Ann Hornaday]], \"The 34 best political movies ever made\" ''The Washington Post'' Jan. 23, 2020)], ranked #24\n\n{{Hal Ashby}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Film}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Being There}}\n[[Category:1979 films]]\n[[Category:1970s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American political satire films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about fictional Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Films about television]]\n[[Category:Films about the media]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Hal Ashby]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Musical or Comedy Actor Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Supporting Actor Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Johnny Mandel]]\n[[Category:Films set in country houses]]\n[[Category:Films set in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Films set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Films shot in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Screenplay BAFTA Award]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n", "name_user": "Lee Leander", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Added link to Film essay pdf on the National Film Registry site under External Links.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Being_There"}
{"title_page": "Legal recognition of sign languages", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe '''legal recognition of sign languages''' differs widely. In some jurisdictions (countries, states, provinces or regions), a [[sign language]] is an official language, whereas in others it has a protected status in certain areas such as education. Governments sometimes stipulate in their constitutions or laws that 'sign language' is recognised or protected, but they fail to specify ''which'' sign language exactly, as there may be several different sign languages in common use within its borders, which has led to problems.\n\nExtending legal recognition is one of the major concerns of the international [[Deaf community]], however, symbolic recognition is no guarantee for an effective improvement of the life of sign language users, and it has been argued that sign languages should be recognized and supported not merely as an accommodation for the disabled, but as the communication medium of language communities.<ref>Sarah C. E. Batterbury. 2012. ''Language Policy'' 11:253\u2013272.</ref>\n\n==Sign language status by state==\n\n===Australia===\n[[Auslan]] was recognised by the Australian Government as a \"community language other than English\" and the preferred language of the Deaf community in policy statements in 1987 and 1991. This recognition does not ensure any provision of services in Auslan, but use of Auslan in Deaf education and provision of Auslan/English interpreters is becoming more common.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|It is now increasingly recognised that signing deaf people constitute a group like any other non-English speaking language group in Australia, with a distinct sub-culture recognised by shared history, social life and sense of identity, united and symbolised by fluency in Auslan, the principal means of communication within the Australian Deaf Community.|||Australia's Language: The Australian Language and Literacy Policy (page 20). (Australian Government Publishing Service, Canberra, 1991)}}\n\n===Austria===\n[[Austrian Sign Language]] (\u00d6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprache, \u00d6GS) was recognised by the Austrian Parliament in 2005. On 1 September 2005 the Austrian Constitution was amended to include a new article: \"\u00a78 (3) Die \u00d6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprache ist als eigenst\u00e4ndige Sprache anerkannt. Das N\u00e4here bestimmen die Gesetze.\u201c (\"Austrian Sign Language is recognised as independent language. The laws will determine the details.\")<ref>Krausneker, Verena (2005) \u00d6sterreichs erste Minderheitensprache, in: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070310204101/http://minderheiten.at/stimme/stimme56f.htmSTIMME von und f\u00fcr Minderheiten # 56]</ref><ref>Krausneker, Verena (2006) ''Taubstumm bis geb\u00e4rdensprachig. Die \u00f6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprachgemeinschaft aus soziolinguistischer Perspektive.'' Verlag Drava.</ref>\n\n===Belgium===\n\n====French Community====\nThe [[Parliament of the French Community|Parliament]] of the [[French Community of Belgium]] recognised [[French Belgian Sign Language]] (LSFB) in a [[decree]] of October 2003. This recognition entails:\n# a cultural (symbolical) recognition and\n# the foundation of a commission that will advise the Government of the French Community in all matters related to LSFB.\n\nIn [https://web.archive.org/web/20041105050456/http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_officiel.pdf ''D\u00e9cret relatif \u00e0 la reconnaissance de la langue des signes''] (Decree on the recognition of the sign language), from three possible legal interpretations of the term 'recognition',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_LS.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2006-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927092446/http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_LS.pdf#page=8 |archive-date=2006-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the following one was retained: \"It concerns a symbolic recognition that goes hand in hand with a general measure, permitting every minister to take action in fields relative to his authority.\"<ref name=\"walloon\">\"... il s'agit d'une reconnaissance cadre assortie d'une mesure d'ex\u00e9cution g\u00e9n\u00e9rale permettant \u00e0 chaque ministre concern\u00e9 de prendre les arr\u00eat\u00e9s d'application relevant de ses comp\u00e9tences ...\"</ref>\n\n====Flemish Community====\n[[Flemish Sign Language]] was recognised on 2006-04-26 by the [[Flemish Parliament]]. This recognition entails:\n# a cultural (symbolical) recognition (see excerpt below),\n# the foundation of a commission that will advise the Flemish government in all matters related to VGT and\n# the structural funding of research and development of VGT.\nThis recognition was accelerated by the most successful petition ever with the Flemish Parliament and the presence of a Deaf member of parliament, Helga Stevens, and her interpreters in the Flemish Parliament.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|Cultural recognition entails that the Flemish Government recognises the Flemish Sign Language as the language of the Deaf Community in Flanders. This 'recognition' encompasses the following three meanings: (1) the Flemish Government acknowledges the correctness of the fact that the Flemish Sign Language is the language of the Deaf Community in Flanders, (2) the Flemish Government also accepts the existence of this language in the judicial domain and treats it accordingly and (3) the Flemish Government expresses its respect for this language.<ref name=\"flemish\">\"Die 'erkenning' omvat hierbij de drie betekennissen van het woord: (1) de Vlaamse overheid bevestigt de juistheid van het feit dat de Vlaamse Gebarentaal de taal is van de Dovengemeenschap in Vlaanderen, (2) de Vlaamse overheid aanvaardt het bestaan van die taal ook op juridisch vlak en behandelt ze als dustanig en (3) de Vlaamse overheid uit haar waardering voor deze taal.\"</ref>|||[http://jsp.vlaamsparlement.be/docs/stukken/2005-2006/g729-1.pdf Decreet houdende de erkenning van de Vlaamse Gebarentaal] (Decree on the recognition of the Flemish Sign Language)}}\n\n===Brazil===\nThe [[Brazilian Sign Language|Brazilian Sign Language (LIBRAS)]] was legally recognized in 2002 but can't replace written [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]];<ref name=\"Brazil 2002\">[http://planalto.gov.br/CCIVIL_03/LEIS/2002/L10436.htm , April 24, 2002].</ref> the law was [[regulation|regulated]] in 2005.<ref name=\"Brazil 2005\">[http://www.planalto.gov.br/ccivil_03/_ato2004-2006/2005/decreto/d5626.htm Brazilian decree n\u00ba 5626, December 22, 2005].</ref> The language must be taught as a part of the [[school of education|education]] and [[speech and language pathology]] curricula, and law also mandates that LIBRAS be an elective subject as part of every other undergraduate course. LIBRAS teachers, instructors and translators are recognized professionals. Schools and health services must provide access (\"[[inclusion (education)|include]]\") to deaf people.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Canada===\nThe [[Accessible Canada Act]], passed on 21 June 2019, recognised '[[American Sign Language]], [[Quebec Sign Language]] and Indigenous sign languages (...) as the primary languages for communication by deaf persons in Canada.'<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://laws.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/A-0.6/page-1.html |title=Accessible Canada Act S.C. 2019, c. 10 |publisher=Canadian Ministry of Justice |date=21 June 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestion Period in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] is interpreted in both [[Quebec Sign Language]] and [[American Sign Language]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} [[Section Fourteen of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms]] specifies that an accused person who does not understand the language in which his or her trial is carried out, or is deaf, is entitled to an interpreter.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn several of Canada's provinces ([[Manitoba]] in 1988, [[Alberta]] in 1990, [[Ontario]] in 1993), [[ASL]] is an officially recognised minority language with legally embedded rights.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOntario recognised ASL and LSQ as a language in which the Deaf can be taught when it altered its Education Act in 1993. Ontario formally recognised ASL in 2007 attributing to it the rights of fellow minority languages.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Inuit Sign Language|Inuit or Inuktitut Sign Language]] (IUR) is used in Canada's arctic communities, and was developed locally by families and communities who found a need for their deaf families and community members. Deaf Inuit who have attended school in Canada's south have also learned ASL. IUR made its debut in Nunavut legislature in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/inuit-sign-language-makes-debut-in-nunavut-legislature-1.772092|title=Inuit sign language makes debut in Nunavut legislature - CBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maritime Sign Language]] (MSL), which derives from the [[British Sign Language]], is a moribund sign language in Canada's [[The Maritimes|Maritime Provinces]].<ref name=CBC>{{cite news |first=Emma |last=Davie |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/preserving-maritime-sign-language-msl-deaf-community-1.5402328 |title=How the deaf community is preserving Maritime Sign Language |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=31 December 2019}}</ref> It does not have any official recognition and is no longer instructed in schools, having been replaced by American Sign Language.<ref name=CBC/> The MSL-teaching [[Halifax School for the Deaf]] operated from 1856 to June 1961, after which the Interprovincial School for the Education of the Deaf (later renamed Atlantic Provinces Special Education Authority, APSEA) in [[Amherst, Nova Scotia]] took over until it closed in 1995.<ref name=CBC/><ref>{{Cite book |last=Marsh |first=James H. |date=1999 |title=The Canadian Encyclopedia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wR_-aSFyvuYC&pg=PA640 |location=Toronto, Ontario |publisher=McClelland & Stewart Inc. |page=640 |isbn=9780771020995 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chile===\nChilean Sign Language (LSCh), Chile enacted in Law No. 20,422, in 2010 in order to ensure the right to equality of opportunity for disabled people, negating any form of discrimination against them. And which recognizes sign language as the natural means of communication of the deaf community.<ref>[http://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idLey=20422 Ley 20422 BCN LEGISLACI\u00d3N CHILENA, 2010]</ref>\n\n===Czech Republic===\n[[Czech Sign Language]] gained legal recognition as a human language with the passage of the Sign Language Law 155/1998 Sb (\"Z\u00e1kon o znakov\u00e9 \u0159e\u010di 155/1998 Sb\").<ref>{{in lang|cs}} {{cite web|url=http://www.sagit.cz/pages/sbirkatxt.asp?zdroj=sb98155&cd=76&typ=r |title=Z\u00c1KON ze dne 11. \u010dervna 1998 o znakov\u00e9 \u0159e\u010di a o zm\u011bn\u011b dal\u0161\u00edch z\u00e1kon\u016f - Sb\u00edrka z\u00e1kon\u016f - Nakladatelstv\u00ed Sagit, a.s |publisher=Sagit.cz |date=2000-12-01 |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\n===Denmark===\n\nAs of 13 May 2014, [[Danish Sign Language]] gained legal recognition. The Danish Parliament established The Danish Sign Language Council \"to devise principles and guidelines for the monitoring of the Danish sign language and offer advice and information on the Danish sign language.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsn.dk/tegnsprog/about-the-danish-sign-language-council|title=The Danish Sign Language Council \u2014 Dansk Sprogn\u00e6vn|website=www.dsn.dk}}</ref>\n\n===European Union===\nThe [[European Parliament]] unanimously approved a resolution about Deaf Sign Languages on 17 June 1988 (available online here<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.policy.hu/flora/ressign2.htm |title=Published by: EUD |publisher=Policy.hu |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>). The resolution indirectly asks all member states for recognition of their sign languages as official languages of the Deaf.\n\n{{cquote|The European Parliament [...] calls on the Commission to make a proposal to the Council concerning official recognition of the sign language used by deaf people in each Member State.|||[http://www.policy.hu/flora/ressign2.htm European Parliament Resolution on Sign Languages 1988]}}\n\nThe EP issued another resolution in 1998 with more or less the same content as in 1988, (see RESOLUTION on sign languages for the deaf, Official Journal C 187, 18/07/1988 P. 0236 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CELEX:51987IP0302:EN:NOT |title=EUR-Lex - 51987IP0302 - EN - EUR-Lex |publisher=Eur-lex.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\nA third resolution was passed in 2016, drafted by Helga Stevens MEP, Europe's first deaf female MEP, a lawyer, and former Executive Director and subsequent President of the European Union of the Deaf. This resolution is on \"Sign language and professional sign language interpreters\". The text in this resolution is more sophisticated than preceding European Parliamentary resolutions, demonstrating the expertise of the author and also the increased maturity of the communities working towards increased recognition of sign language (e.g. drawing on academic expertise in Deaf Studies, interpreting studies, linguistics, etc.)<ref>http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/TA-8-2016-0442_EN.html</ref>\n\n===Finland===\n[[Finnish Sign Language]] was recognised in the constitution in August 1995.\n\n{{cquote|''Section 17 - Right to one's language and culture'' [...] The rights of persons using sign language and of persons in need of interpretation or translation aid owing to disability shall be guaranteed by an Act.<ref name=\"finnish\">17 \u00a7 Oikeus omaan kieleen ja kulttuuriin [...] Viittomakielt\u00e4 k\u00e4ytt\u00e4vien sek\u00e4 vammaisuuden vuoksi tulkitsemisja k\u00e4\u00e4nn\u00f6sapua tarvitsevien oikeudet turvataan lailla. (Ministry of Justice, Finland: [http://www.finlex.fi/linkit/ajansd/19990731000 ''Suomen perustuslaki''].)</ref>|||[http://www.om.fi/uploads/54begu60narbnv_1.pdf The Constitution of Finland]}}\n\n===Iceland===\n[[Icelandic Sign Language]] was recognised by law in education in 2004.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|This National Curriculum Guide contains, for the first time, provisions on special Icelandic instruction for students whose mother tongue is not Icelandic. There are also new provisions on special Icelandic instruction for deaf and hearing-impaired pupils and sign-language instruction for the deaf. The objectives for Icelandic instruction of immigrants and the deaf and of sign-language instruction fall under the subject area of language arts (Icelandic) in compulsory school. [...]\n\nSign language is of basic importance for the development of language, personality and thinking of deaf children. For the deaf, sign language is the most important source of knowledge and their route to participation in Icelandic culture and the culture of the deaf. Sign language is of great importance for all school work and for the pupils' life and work.<ref name=\"icelandic\">\u00cd a\u00f0aln\u00e1mskr\u00e1 grunnsk\u00f3la eru \u00ed fyrsta sinn sett \u00e1kv\u00e6\u00f0i um s\u00e9rstaka \u00edslenskukennslu fyrir nemendur me\u00f0 anna\u00f0 m\u00f3\u00f0urm\u00e1l en \u00edslensku. Einnig eru n\u00fd \u00e1kv\u00e6\u00f0i um s\u00e9rstaka \u00edslenskukennslu fyrir heyrnarlausa og heyrnarskerta nemendur og t\u00e1knm\u00e1lskennslu fyrir heyrnarlausa. Markmi\u00f0 fyrir \u00edslenskukennslu n\u00fdb\u00faa og heyrnarlausra og t\u00e1knm\u00e1lskennslu falla undir n\u00e1mssvi\u00f0 \u00edslensku \u00ed grunnsk\u00f3la. [...]\n\nT\u00e1knm\u00e1l hefur grundvallar\u00fe\u00fd\u00f0ingu fyrir \u00feroska m\u00e1ls, pers\u00f3nuleika og hugsunar heyrnarlausra nemenda. Hj\u00e1 heyrnarlausum er t\u00e1knm\u00e1li\u00f0 mikilv\u00e6gasta uppspretta \u00feekkingar og lei\u00f0 til a\u00f0 taka \u00fe\u00e1tt \u00ed \u00edslenskri menningu og menningu heyrnarlausra. T\u00e1knm\u00e1li\u00f0 hefur mikla \u00fe\u00fd\u00f0ingu fyrir alla vinnu \u00ed sk\u00f3lanum og fyrir l\u00edf og starf nemendanna. (Ministry of Education, Science and Culture: [http://bella.stjr.is/utgafur/AGalmennurhluti.pdf ''A\u00f0aln\u00e1mskr\u00e1 grunnsk\u00f3la: Almennur hluti''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927194051/http://bella.stjr.is/utgafur/AGalmennurhluti.pdf |date=2007-09-27 }})</ref>|||4=[http://bella.mrn.stjr.is/utgafur/general.pdf#page=23 The National Curriculum Guide for Compulsory School (Ministry of Education, Science and Culture, 2004)] (official translation)}}\n\nOn 27 May 2011, the Icelandic Parliament unanimously approved a bill which recognises Icelandic Sign Language as an official minority language with constitutional rights and as the first language of the deaf people of [[Iceland]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Indian subcontinent===\nThere is no official recognition of [[Indo-Pakistani Sign Language]] (IPSL), which is well-documented, widely used throughout the [[Indian subcontinent]] across national and state borders with few regional variations, and has over a million estimated users in [[India]] alone, is also commonly used in [[Pakistan]] and probably also in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Evans |first=Nicholas |title=Reciprocals and Semantic Typology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U020QQv1Qn4C&pg=PA95 |location=Amsterdam & Philadelphia |publisher=John Benjamins Publishing |page=95 |isbn=9789027206794 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Ireland===\nIrish Sign Language was given official recognition in 2017. The \"Recognition of Irish Sign Language for the Deaf Community Bill 2016\" passed all stages in the [[Oireachtas]] (Irish Parliament) on 14 December 2017, and was signed into law by the [[President of Ireland]] [[Michael D. Higgins|Michael D Higgins]] on 24 December 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/irish-sign-language-given-official-legal-recognition-1.3338081|title=Irish Sign Language given official legal recognition|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2017/1224/929482-sign-language-bill/|title=President signs Irish Sign Language bill into law|date=2017-12-24|work=RTE.ie|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en}}</ref> Prior to 2017, there was no automatic right for deaf people to have an ISL [[Language interpretation|interpreter]] (except for criminal court proceedings). For the deaf community, recognition of ISL means more legal rights and better access to [[public service]]s - including [[Education in the Republic of Ireland|education]], [[Healthcare in the Republic of Ireland|healthcare]], [[Media of the Republic of Ireland|media]] and [[banking]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2017/1213/927259-irish-sign-language/|title=D\u00e1il passes 'historic' sign language legislation|date=2017-12-14|work=RTE.ie|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/irish-sign-language-set-to-be-given-official-status-36407921.html|title=Irish Sign Language set to be given official status - Independent.ie|work=Independent.ie|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/irish-sign-language-set-to-receive-official-recognition-818648.html|title=Irish sign language set to receive official recognition|date=2017-12-14|work=Breaking News|access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref>\n\n===Italy===\nThere is no official recognition of [[Italian Sign Language]] (''Lingua dei Segni Italiana'', LIS) yet. Those who oppose LIS recognition say this language is \"grammarless,\" although, by definition, a [[Language#The properties of language|language]] cannot be, in fact, grammarless. Several research on the matter have already shown that [[Italian Sign Language]] is a proper language.<ref>[http://michelebrunelli.interfree.it/GrammLIS_e_Restrittive.pdf Michele Brunelli: Grammatica della LIS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722035622/http://michelebrunelli.interfree.it/GrammLIS_e_Restrittive.pdf |date=2011-07-22 }}</ref>\n\n===Kenya===\nThe 2010 [[Constitution of Kenya]] recognises [[Kenyan Sign Language]] and states that the state shall promote the development and use of Kenyan Sign Language (Article 7.3b). Sign language is recognised further in Article 120 (1) which states that 'the official languages of Parliament are [[Swahili language|Kiswahili]], [[English language|English]] and Kenyan Sign Language and the business of Parliament may be conducted in English, Kiswahili and Kenyan Sign Language.'<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://kenyalaw.org:8181/exist/kenyalex/actview.xql?actid=Const2010 |title=Constitution of Kenya, 2010 |work=Kenya Law |publisher=Judiciary of Kenya |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Malta ===\nThe [[Maltese Sign Language]] (LSM) was official recognized by parliament in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/63266/parliament_gives_maltese_sign_language_official_recognition|title=Parliament gives Maltese sign language official recognition}}</ref>\n\n=== Mexico ===\n\nThe [[Mexican Sign Language]] (LSM) was officially declared a \"national language\" in 2003, and it started being used in public deaf education thereafter.<ref>Ley Federal para las Personas con Discapacidad.  http://www.diputados.gob.mx/LeyesBiblio/pdf/262.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150616003344/http://www.diputados.gob.mx/LeyesBiblio/pdf/262.pdf |date=2015-06-16 }}</ref> Before 2003, deaf education in the country was focused on oralism (speech and lipreading) with few schools conducting classes in LSM.<ref>Karla Faurot, Dianne Dellinger, Andy Eatough, Steve Parkhurst (1992, revised 1998 and 2001) The identity of Mexican sign as a language. http://www.sil.org/silesr/2000/2000-002/ \u00a9 1999 Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\nAlthough [[Nepali Sign Language]] has not yet been officially recognized as the [[mother tongue]] of Nepal's deaf population, legislation is underway which will bring Nepali law in line with the provisions of the UN [[Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities]]. These laws will recognize the rights of the deaf to use [[Nepali Sign Language]] have it used in education, in social life, in the legal sphere, etc., and this should thus lead to official governmental recognition of [[Nepali Sign Language]] on a par with the various spoken languages of Nepal.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Netherlands===\n[[File:Nederlandse gebarentaal krijgt eindelijk een zichtbare plek in onze samenleving.webm|thumb|[[Roelof van Laar]] explaining the 2016 bill to recognise NGT]]\nThe [[Dutch Sign Language]] (NGT) has not been recognised officially by law. In 2010, the [[Christian Union (Netherlands)|Christian Union]] party introduced a bill to recognise NGT, but it did not pass.<ref name=\"AD2016\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.ad.nl/nieuws/erken-nederlandse-gebarentaal-als-officiele-taal~a5a253f6/ |title=Erken Nederlandse gebarentaal als offici\u00eble taal |publisher=Algemeen Dagblad |date=3 October 2016 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref>\nIn October 2016, this was followed by a bill from MPs [[Roelof van Laar]] ([[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour Party]]) and [[Carla Dik-Faber]] (Christian Union) for legal recognition of NGT as an official language.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2016/10/03/gebarentaal-moet-erkend-worden-als-officiele-taal-a1524573|title=PvdA en CU: erken gebarentaal als offici\u00eble taal|author=Beila Heilbron|publisher=NRC Handelsblad|date=3 October 2016 |language=nl}}</ref> After Van Laar's departure, MP [[Attje Kuiken]] (Labour Party) took over the bill in September 2019, while MP [[Jessica van Eijs]] ([[Democrats 66]]) joined Kuiken and Dik-Faber.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.eerstekamer.nl/behandeling/20190927/brief_lid_fractie_brief_van_de/document3/f=/vl29hrq7v1yn.pdf |title=Voorstel van wet van de leden Van Laar en Dik-Faber ter erkenning van Nederlandse gebarentaal (Wet erkenning Nederlandse gebarentaal) |author=Attje Kuiken & Carla Dik-Faber |work=Brief van de leden Kuiken en Dik-Faber |publisher=Senate of the Netherlands |date=27 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nos.nl/nieuwsuur/artikel/2300498-initiatiefwet-nederlandse-gebarentaal-erkennen-als-officiele-taal.html |title=Initiatiefwet: Nederlandse Gebarentaal erkennen als offici\u00eble taal |author=Linda de Groot |work=Nieuwsuur |publisher=NOS |date=5 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref> At the end of September 2019 the Advisory Division of the [[Council of State (Netherlands)|Council of State]] stated that the text of the bill was still too vague, as it did not make clear which problems it exactly intended to address and through which practical means; for example, it asked whether 'the Deaf culture' \u2013 mentioned in the bill \u2013 also needed to be legally recognised, and if so, what that term precisely entailed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.raadvanstate.nl/@117458/samenvatting-gebarentaal/ |title=Samenvatting advies initiatiefwetsvoorstel erkenning Nederlandse gebarentaal |publisher=Advisory Division of the Council of State |date=30 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\n[[New Zealand Sign Language]] became the third official language of [[New Zealand]] in April 2006, joining [[M\u0101ori language|English and M\u0101ori]] when the bill was passed in the New Zealand Parliament on 6 April 2006.<ref>McKee, R. 2007. The eyes have it! Our third official language\u2013New Zealand Sign Language. ''Journal of New Zealand Studies'', NS 4-5.129-148.</ref>\n\n{{cquote|Part 2 cl 6: New Zealand Sign Language is declared to be an official language of New Zealand.|||[http://www.odi.govt.nz/documents/nzds/nzsl-bill.pdf New Zealand Sign Language Bill]}}\n\n=== North Macedonia ===\nThe [[Macedonian Sign Language]] (''\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043d \u0458\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, Makedonski znakoven jazik'') is officially recognized as \"natural way of communication between the people\". The language is regulated by a law, which allows students and every individual in [[North Macedonia]] to study the language. Also, the law secures the right of interpreter for the students with special needs, and every other deaf person can request an interpreter, as well.<ref name=\"\u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\">''[http://www.deafmkd.org.mk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=57&Itemid=82&lang=mk \u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0437\u0430 \u0443\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \u043d\u0430  \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043e\u0442 \u0458\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0435\u043d \u0432\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430, \u0431\u0440\u043e\u0458 105, 21 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442 2009, \u0421\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0458\u0435]''</ref> Currently,{{when|date=April 2020}} there are more than 6.000 Macedonian citizens with deafness.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Northern Ireland===\nIn Northern Ireland, both [[British Sign Language]] and [[Irish Sign Language]] (but not [[Northern Ireland Sign Language]]) were recognised as official languages by the [[Northern Ireland Office]] in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nio.gov.uk/paul-murphy-announces-recognition-for-sign-language/media-detail.htm?newsID=8540 |title=Paul Murphy announces recognition for sign language |accessdate=2008-06-22 |date=2004-03-30 |publisher=[[Northern Ireland Office]] |quote=I am pleased to announce formal recognition for both British and Irish Sign Languages in Northern Ireland. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520115301/http://www.nio.gov.uk/paul-murphy-announces-recognition-for-sign-language/media-detail.htm?newsID=8540 |archivedate=2011-05-20 }}</ref> but they don't yet have the same status as the province's two official minority languages, [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[Ulster Scots language|Ulster-Scots]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Norway===\n[[Norwegian Sign Language]] is recognised by law in education.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Papua New Guinea===\nIn May 2015, [[Papua New Guinean Sign Language]] became the fourth official language of [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref name=\"sil.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sil.org/about/news/two-sign-languages-given-official-language-status|title=Two Sign Languages Given Official Language Status|date=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Philippines ===\nArticle 3 of Republic Act No. 11106 declared [[Filipino Sign Language]] as the national sign language of the [[Philippines]], specifying that it shall be recognized, supported and promoted as the medium of official communication in all transactions involving the deaf, and as the language of instruction of deaf education.<ref>{{cite act |url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/downloads/2018/10oct/20181030-RA-11106-RRD.pdf|title=The Filipino Sign Language Act|type=Republic act|number=11106|article=3|work=Official Gazette |publisher=Government of the Philippines|date=30 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Genalyn Kabiling |work=Manila Bulletin |title=Filipino Sign Language declared as nat\u2019l sign language of Filipino deaf |date=12 November 2018 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2018/11/12/filipino-sign-language-declared-as-natl-sign-language-of-filipino-deaf/ |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Portugal===\n{{cquote|Art. 74, 2 (h): In implementing the education policy, the state shall be charged with protecting and developing Portuguese sign language, as an expression of culture and an instrument for access to education and equal opportunities.<ref name=\"portuguese\">Na realiza\u00e7\u00e3o da pol\u00edtica de ensino incumbe ao Estado proteger e valorizar a l\u00edngua gestual portuguesa, enquanto express\u00e3o cultural e instrumento de acesso \u00e0 educa\u00e7\u00e3o e da igualdade de oportunidades. (Assembleia da Rep\u00fablica: [http://www.parlamento.pt/const_leg/crp_port/index.html Constitui\u00e7\u00e3o da rep\u00fablica portuguesa] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809203630/http://www.parlamento.pt/const_leg/crp_port/index.html |date=2007-08-09 }}</ref>|||[http://www.parlamento.pt/ingles/cons_leg/crp_ing/ Constitution of Portugal]}}\nAs an example, many shows (such as the news) in public channels ([[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]]) have one corner of the screen with a person translating what's being said into sign language.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n===Russia===\nRussian Sign Language (''\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0436\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a'') has very limited legal recognition. In accordance with the Federal \"Law on Protection of People with Disabilities\" the sign language is considered a language used for inter-personal communication only, which means that no state support for the language is provided.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\n=== Slovak Republic ===\n[[Slovak Sign Language]] was recognised in 1995 by law: \"Z\u00e1kon o posunkovej re\u010di nepo\u010duj\u00facich os\u00f4b 149/1995 Sb\" - the Law of the Sign Language of the Deaf 149/1995.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== South Africa ===\n[[South African Sign Language]] is not specifically recognised as a [[Languages of South Africa|Language of South Africa]] by the country's [[Constitution of South Africa|constitution]], instead it contains the phrase \"sign language\" in the generic sense.<ref>http://www.info.gov.za/documents/constitution/1996/96cons1.htm#6 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629092124/http://www.info.gov.za/documents/constitution/1996/96cons1.htm |date=2011-06-29 }}</ref>\nThere is a process underway in parliament to investigate the possibility of upgrading the status of SASL to become the country's 12th official language.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pmg.org.za/report/20091113-language-issues-proposed-recognition-south-african-sign-language-offi |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-10-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100515104619/http://www.pmg.org.za/report/20091113-language-issues-proposed-recognition-south-african-sign-language-offi |archive-date=2010-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\nOn 31 December 2015, the \"South Korean National Assembly passed legislation to recognize Korean Sign Language as one of Korea\u2019s official languages.\"<ref name=\"sil.org\"/>\n\n=== Spain ===\nOn 28 June 2007, Spanish and Catalan Sign Languages were recognised by the Spanish Parliament to be official languages in Spain. This recent legal development has opened a door to reinforced communication in the areas of healthcare, justice, education and MCM.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nSo far, the [[Autonomous communities of Spain|Autonomous Communities]] of [[Catalonia]], [[Andalusia]], and [[Valencia (autonomous community)|Valencia]] had granted the use of sign languages to the Deaf. In the other Spanish regions no sign languages were so far recognised, and support in terms of sign language interpretation for Deaf persons has been minimal or confined by different budgets. As pointed out, there are three sign languages claimed by Deaf organisations: [[Spanish Sign Language]], [[Catalan Sign Language]] (LSC) and [[Valencian Sign Language]] (LSPV), although some linguists consider these to be the same.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Catalonia====\nAlthough a regional law guarantees the presence of [[Catalan Sign Language]] since 1994 in all areas under the Catalan Government, such as education and media, until recently it was officially recognised the LSC in the [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia]] of 2006.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Andalusia====\nThe legal situation in Andalusia is similar to the one in Catalonia, where a regional Law guarantees the presence of the [[Spanish Sign Language]] (LSE) in all social scopes since 1998. Recently, a recognition of it is included in the reforming of their Statute of Autonomy. At the moment, Andalusia is the unique Community where LSE is recognised with regards to the rest of Spain. In any case, in linguistic terms, the LSE used there has a strong dialectal variation.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Valencia====\nUntil recently, Valencia had poor legal support for the Deaf. The approved 2006 Statute of Autonomy grants to Valencian Deaf their right to use [[Valencian Sign Language]] (LSPV or LSCV). (Though the statute refers only to \"sign language\" in a generic sense.){{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|Article 13,4: The Generalitat shall grant the use of the own sign language of deaf persons, which shall have to be purposed in education, protection and respect.<ref name=\"valencian\">La Generalitat garantir\u00e0 l\u2019\u00fas de la llengua de signes pr\u00f2pia de les persones sordes, que haur\u00e0 de ser objecte d\u2019ensenyament, protecci\u00f3 i respecte. (Corts Valencianes: [http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf Estatut d'Autonomia de la Communitat Valenciana] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926130504/http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf |date=2007-09-26 }}.)</ref>|||[http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf Statute of Autonomy of the Valencian Country]}}\n\n====Galicia====\n[[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] is said{{by whom|date=June 2012}} to be working on a bill concerning the recognition of a sign language.{{citation needed|date=June 2012}}\n\n=== Sri Lanka ===\nThe recognition of [[Sri Lankan sign languages|Sri Lankan Sign Language]] was accepted by [[Sri Lanka]] on 26 September 2010. According to the report by [[Sri Lanka]]n Newspaper at Internet on 23 September 2010[<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.colombopage.com/archive_10B/Sep23_1285222003KA.php|title = Sign language recognized in Sri Lanka|website = Colombo Page|date = 23 September 2010|location = Colombo, Sri Lanka}}</ref>]\n\n===Thailand===\n[[Thai Sign Language]] was acknowledged as \"the national language of deaf people in Thailand\" on 17 August 1999, in a resolution signed by the Permanent Secretary for Education on behalf of the Royal Thai Government that affirmed the rights of deaf people to learn this distinct sign language as their first language at home and in schools. According to a  [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231953/http://pr.gallaudet.edu/otg/BackIssues.asp?ID=3810 report by Charles Reilly (1999)], \"specific actions will be taken by the government, including hiring deaf people as teachers and instructors of sign language in deaf schools, and providing interpreters for deaf people in higher education.\"\n\n===Turkey===\nThere is currently{{when|date=April 2020}} no official recognition of the [[Turkish Sign Language]], the de facto sign language in use by the Turkish deaf community.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 1 July 2005, the [[Turkish Grand National Assembly]] enacted an updated [[disability discrimination act|Disability Law]] (No. 5378), which for the first time in Turkish law made references to sign language. Law no. 15 says that a sign language is to be used in the deaf education system, and law no. 30 says that sign language interpreting is to be provided to deaf people.<ref>http://majordomo.valenciacc.edu/hypermail/slling-l/0508/0013.html{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, these laws are yet to be implemented (as of 2007), and it remains to be seen what form of sign language, if any, will be supported. There has been some discussion in parliament about \"developing\" a standardised sign language.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abgs.gov.tr/tarama/tarama_files/19/SC19DET_People%20with%20disabilities.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2007-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070404073157/http://www.abgs.gov.tr/tarama/tarama_files/19/SC19DET_People%20with%20disabilities.pdf |archive-date=2007-04-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTurkey also has action plans for disability issues, such as the Employment of Disabled Persons Plan (2005\u20132010) and the Prevention of Discrimination Against Disabled Persons Plan (2006\u20132010).{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Uganda===\nOn 8 October 1995, [[Uganda]] adopted a new constitution that included a mention that 'The State shall [...] promote the development of a sign language for the deaf'.<ref>[[World Federation of the Deaf|WFD]] News, April 1996.</ref> It does not specify the [[Ugandan Sign Language]] as being the intented language. A Deaf signer, 27-year-old [[Alex Ndeezi]], was elected to [[Parliament of Uganda|parliament]] in 1996.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|XXIV (iii). The State shall [...] promote the development of a sign language for the deaf.\"|4=[http://www.parliament.go.ug/index.php?option=com_wrapper&Itemid=78 \"National Objectives and Directive Principles of State Policy\", Constitution of Uganda]}}\n\n===United States of America===\nThe Federal government does not recognize any language spoken or signed as an official language. However many individual states have laws recognizing [[American Sign Language]] as a \"foreign language\"; some recognize ASL as a language of instruction in schools.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} A number of U.S. universities accept ASL credit to fulfill foreign language requirements.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unm.edu/~wilcox/UNM/univlist.html |title=Universities That Accept ASL in Fulfillment of Foreign Language Requirements |publisher=University of New Mexico |last=Wilcox |first=Sherman}}</ref>\n\n===Uruguay===\n\nAlthough there are no \"official\" languages in Uruguay, nevertheless, Lengua de Se\u00f1as Uruguaya, or \"LSU\" (In English: \"Uruguayan Sign Language\"), was \"recognized\" as the language of deaf persons in 2001 by the law.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110704041632/http://200.40.229.134/IndexDB/Leyes/ConsultaLeyes.asp LEY No. 17.378.] ''Recon\u00f3cese a todos los efectos a la Lengua de Se\u00f1as Uruguaya como la lengua natural de las personas sordas y de sus comunidades en todo el territorio de la Rep\u00fablica.''  10 de Julio de 2001.  Parlamento del Uruguay.</ref>\n\nIn the 2008 law 18.437 (\"Ley General de Educaci\u00f3n. 12 de Diciembre de 2008\"), LSU is \"considered\" to be one of the mother tongues of Uruguayan citizens (along with Uruguayan Spanish and Uruguayan Portuguese. In the policy documents of the Comisi\u00f3n de Pol\u00edticas Ling\u00fc\u00edsticas en la Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica (the Public Education Language Policy Commission, which is part of the Administraci\u00f3n Nacional de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica, ANEP) it is proposed that LSU would be the principal language of deaf education.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Venezuela===\n[[Venezuelan Sign Language]] was recognised in the country's [[Constitution of Venezuela|constitution]] on 12 November 1999.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Zimbabwe===\nThe various [[Zimbabwean sign languages]], grouped together as \"sign language\", are recognised in the 2013 [[Constitution of Zimbabwe]] as one of the sixteen \"officially recognised languages of Zimbabwe\".<ref name=\"constitution\">\"The following languages, namely Chewa, Chibarwe, English, Kalanga, Koisan, Nambya, Ndau, Ndebele, Shangani, Shona, sign language, Sotho, Tonga, Tswana, Venda and Xhosa, are the officially recognised languages of Zimbabwe.\"  ([http://www.kubatana.net/docs/legisl/constitution_zim_draft_copac_130125.pdf Chapter 1, section 6, CONSTITUTION OF ZIMBABWE (final draft)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002110534/http://www.kubatana.net/docs/legisl/constitution_zim_draft_copac_130125.pdf |date=2013-10-02 }}).</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060216150733/http://fevlado.be/themas/gebarentaal/documenten/Status%20van%20gebarentalen%20in%20Europa.pdf Report on the status of Sign Languages in Europe] (PDF link)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050920061758/http://www.deafcouncil.org.uk/drcsub.htm Official Recognition of British Sign Language]\n\n{{sign language navigation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legal Recognition of Sign Languages}}\n[[Category:Sign language]]\n[[Category:Language policy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe '''legal recognition of sign languages''' differs widely. In some jurisdictions (countries, states, provinces or regions), a [[sign language]] is an official language, whereas in others it has a protected status in certain areas such as education. Governments sometimes stipulate in their constitutions or laws that 'sign language' is recognised or protected, but they fail to specify ''which'' sign language exactly, as there may be several different sign languages in common use within its borders, which has led to problems.\n\nExtending legal recognition is one of the major concerns of the international [[Deaf community]], however, symbolic recognition is no guarantee for an effective improvement of the life of sign language users, and it has been argued that sign languages should be recognized and supported not merely as an accommodation for the disabled, but as the communication medium of language communities.<ref>Sarah C. E. Batterbury. 2012. ''Language Policy'' 11:253\u2013272.</ref>\n\n==Sign language status by state==\n\n===Australia===\n[[Auslan]] was recognised by the Australian Government as a \"community language other than English\" and the preferred language of the Deaf community in policy statements in 1987 and 1991. This recognition does not ensure any provision of services in Auslan, but use of Auslan in Deaf education and provision of Auslan/English interpreters is becoming more common.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|It is now increasingly recognised that signing deaf people constitute a group like any other non-English speaking language group in Australia, with a distinct sub-culture recognised by shared history, social life and sense of identity, united and symbolised by fluency in Auslan, the principal means of communication within the Australian Deaf Community.|||Australia's Language: The Australian Language and Literacy Policy (page 20). (Australian Government Publishing Service, Canberra, 1991)}}\n\n===Austria===\n[[Austrian Sign Language]] (\u00d6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprache, \u00d6GS) was recognised by the Austrian Parliament in 2005. On 1 September 2005 the Austrian Constitution was amended to include a new article: \"\u00a78 (3) Die \u00d6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprache ist als eigenst\u00e4ndige Sprache anerkannt. Das N\u00e4here bestimmen die Gesetze.\u201c (\"Austrian Sign Language is recognised as independent language. The laws will determine the details.\")<ref>Krausneker, Verena (2005) \u00d6sterreichs erste Minderheitensprache, in: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070310204101/http://minderheiten.at/stimme/stimme56f.htmSTIMME von und f\u00fcr Minderheiten # 56]</ref><ref>Krausneker, Verena (2006) ''Taubstumm bis geb\u00e4rdensprachig. Die \u00f6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprachgemeinschaft aus soziolinguistischer Perspektive.'' Verlag Drava.</ref>\n\n===Belgium===\n\n====French Community====\nThe [[Parliament of the French Community|Parliament]] of the [[French Community of Belgium]] recognised [[French Belgian Sign Language]] (LSFB) in a [[decree]] of October 2003. This recognition entails:\n# a cultural (symbolical) recognition and\n# the foundation of a commission that will advise the Government of the French Community in all matters related to LSFB.\n\nIn [https://web.archive.org/web/20041105050456/http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_officiel.pdf ''D\u00e9cret relatif \u00e0 la reconnaissance de la langue des signes''] (Decree on the recognition of the sign language), from three possible legal interpretations of the term 'recognition',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_LS.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2006-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927092446/http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_LS.pdf#page=8 |archive-date=2006-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the following one was retained: \"It concerns a symbolic recognition that goes hand in hand with a general measure, permitting every minister to take action in fields relative to his authority.\"<ref name=\"walloon\">\"... il s'agit d'une reconnaissance cadre assortie d'une mesure d'ex\u00e9cution g\u00e9n\u00e9rale permettant \u00e0 chaque ministre concern\u00e9 de prendre les arr\u00eat\u00e9s d'application relevant de ses comp\u00e9tences ...\"</ref>\n\n====Flemish Community====\n[[Flemish Sign Language]] was recognised on 2006-04-26 by the [[Flemish Parliament]]. This recognition entails:\n# a cultural (symbolical) recognition (see excerpt below),\n# the foundation of a commission that will advise the Flemish government in all matters related to VGT and\n# the structural funding of research and development of VGT.\nThis recognition was accelerated by the most successful petition ever with the Flemish Parliament and the presence of a Deaf member of parliament, Helga Stevens, and her interpreters in the Flemish Parliament.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|Cultural recognition entails that the Flemish Government recognises the Flemish Sign Language as the language of the Deaf Community in Flanders. This 'recognition' encompasses the following three meanings: (1) the Flemish Government acknowledges the correctness of the fact that the Flemish Sign Language is the language of the Deaf Community in Flanders, (2) the Flemish Government also accepts the existence of this language in the judicial domain and treats it accordingly and (3) the Flemish Government expresses its respect for this language.<ref name=\"flemish\">\"Die 'erkenning' omvat hierbij de drie betekennissen van het woord: (1) de Vlaamse overheid bevestigt de juistheid van het feit dat de Vlaamse Gebarentaal de taal is van de Dovengemeenschap in Vlaanderen, (2) de Vlaamse overheid aanvaardt het bestaan van die taal ook op juridisch vlak en behandelt ze als dustanig en (3) de Vlaamse overheid uit haar waardering voor deze taal.\"</ref>|||[http://jsp.vlaamsparlement.be/docs/stukken/2005-2006/g729-1.pdf Decreet houdende de erkenning van de Vlaamse Gebarentaal] (Decree on the recognition of the Flemish Sign Language)}}\n\n===Brazil===\nThe [[Brazilian Sign Language|Brazilian Sign Language (LIBRAS)]] was legally recognized in 2002 but can't replace written [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]];<ref name=\"Brazil 2002\">[http://planalto.gov.br/CCIVIL_03/LEIS/2002/L10436.htm , April 24, 2002].</ref> the law was [[regulation|regulated]] in 2005.<ref name=\"Brazil 2005\">[http://www.planalto.gov.br/ccivil_03/_ato2004-2006/2005/decreto/d5626.htm Brazilian decree n\u00ba 5626, December 22, 2005].</ref> The language must be taught as a part of the [[school of education|education]] and [[speech and language pathology]] curricula, and law also mandates that LIBRAS be an elective subject as part of every other undergraduate course. LIBRAS teachers, instructors and translators are recognized professionals. Schools and health services must provide access (\"[[inclusion (education)|include]]\") to deaf people.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Canada===\nThe [[Accessible Canada Act]], passed on 21 June 2019, recognised '[[American Sign Language]], [[Quebec Sign Language]] and Indigenous sign languages (...) as the primary languages for communication by deaf persons in Canada.'<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://laws.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/A-0.6/page-1.html |title=Accessible Canada Act S.C. 2019, c. 10 |publisher=Canadian Ministry of Justice |date=21 June 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestion Period in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] is interpreted in both [[Quebec Sign Language]] and [[American Sign Language]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} [[Section Fourteen of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms]] specifies that an accused person who does not understand the language in which his or her trial is carried out, or is deaf, is entitled to an interpreter.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn several of Canada's provinces ([[Manitoba]] in 1988, [[Alberta]] in 1990, [[Ontario]] in 1993), [[ASL]] is an officially recognised minority language with legally embedded rights.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOntario recognised ASL and LSQ as a language in which the Deaf can be taught when it altered its Education Act in 1993. Ontario formally recognised ASL in 2007 attributing to it the rights of fellow minority languages.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Inuit Sign Language|Inuit or Inuktitut Sign Language]] (IUR) is used in Canada's arctic communities, and was developed locally by families and communities who found a need for their deaf families and community members. Deaf Inuit who have attended school in Canada's south have also learned ASL. IUR made its debut in Nunavut legislature in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/inuit-sign-language-makes-debut-in-nunavut-legislature-1.772092|title=Inuit sign language makes debut in Nunavut legislature - CBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maritime Sign Language]] (MSL), which derives from the [[British Sign Language]], is a moribund sign language in Canada's [[The Maritimes|Maritime Provinces]].<ref name=CBC>{{cite news |first=Emma |last=Davie |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/preserving-maritime-sign-language-msl-deaf-community-1.5402328 |title=How the deaf community is preserving Maritime Sign Language |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=31 December 2019}}</ref> It does not have any official recognition and is no longer instructed in schools, having been replaced by American Sign Language.<ref name=CBC/> The MSL-teaching [[Halifax School for the Deaf]] operated from 1856 to June 1961, after which the Interprovincial School for the Education of the Deaf (later renamed Atlantic Provinces Special Education Authority, APSEA) in [[Amherst, Nova Scotia]] took over until it closed in 1995.<ref name=CBC/><ref>{{Cite book |last=Marsh |first=James H. |date=1999 |title=The Canadian Encyclopedia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wR_-aSFyvuYC&pg=PA640 |location=Toronto, Ontario |publisher=McClelland & Stewart Inc. |page=640 |isbn=9780771020995 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chile===\nChilean Sign Language (LSCh), Chile enacted in Law No. 20,422, in 2010 in order to ensure the right to equality of opportunity for disabled people, negating any form of discrimination against them. And which recognizes sign language as the natural means of communication of the deaf community.<ref>[http://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idLey=20422 Ley 20422 BCN LEGISLACI\u00d3N CHILENA, 2010]</ref>\n\n===Czech Republic===\n[[Czech Sign Language]] gained legal recognition as a human language with the passage of the Sign Language Law 155/1998 Sb (\"Z\u00e1kon o znakov\u00e9 \u0159e\u010di 155/1998 Sb\").<ref>{{in lang|cs}} {{cite web|url=http://www.sagit.cz/pages/sbirkatxt.asp?zdroj=sb98155&cd=76&typ=r |title=Z\u00c1KON ze dne 11. \u010dervna 1998 o znakov\u00e9 \u0159e\u010di a o zm\u011bn\u011b dal\u0161\u00edch z\u00e1kon\u016f - Sb\u00edrka z\u00e1kon\u016f - Nakladatelstv\u00ed Sagit, a.s |publisher=Sagit.cz |date=2000-12-01 |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\n===Denmark===\n\nAs of 13 May 2014, [[Danish Sign Language]] gained legal recognition. The Danish Parliament established The Danish Sign Language Council \"to devise principles and guidelines for the monitoring of the Danish sign language and offer advice and information on the Danish sign language.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsn.dk/tegnsprog/about-the-danish-sign-language-council|title=The Danish Sign Language Council \u2014 Dansk Sprogn\u00e6vn|website=www.dsn.dk}}</ref>\n\n===European Union===\nThe [[European Parliament]] unanimously approved a resolution about Deaf Sign Languages on 17 June 1988 (available online here<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.policy.hu/flora/ressign2.htm |title=Published by: EUD |publisher=Policy.hu |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>). The resolution indirectly asks all member states for recognition of their sign languages as official languages of the Deaf.\n\n{{cquote|The European Parliament [...] calls on the Commission to make a proposal to the Council concerning official recognition of the sign language used by deaf people in each Member State.|||[http://www.policy.hu/flora/ressign2.htm European Parliament Resolution on Sign Languages 1988]}}\n\nThe EP issued another resolution in 1998 with more or less the same content as in 1988, (see RESOLUTION on sign languages for the deaf, Official Journal C 187, 18/07/1988 P. 0236 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CELEX:51987IP0302:EN:NOT |title=EUR-Lex - 51987IP0302 - EN - EUR-Lex |publisher=Eur-lex.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\nA third resolution was passed in 2016, drafted by Helga Stevens MEP, Europe's first deaf female MEP, a lawyer, and former Executive Director and subsequent President of the European Union of the Deaf. This resolution is on \"Sign language and professional sign language interpreters\". The text in this resolution is more sophisticated than preceding European Parliamentary resolutions, demonstrating the expertise of the author and also the increased maturity of the communities working towards increased recognition of sign language (e.g. drawing on academic expertise in Deaf Studies, interpreting studies, linguistics, etc.)<ref>http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/TA-8-2016-0442_EN.html</ref>\n\n===Finland===\n[[Finnish Sign Language]] was recognised in the constitution in August 1995.\n\n{{cquote|''Section 17 - Right to one's language and culture'' [...] The rights of persons using sign language and of persons in need of interpretation or translation aid owing to disability shall be guaranteed by an Act.<ref name=\"finnish\">17 \u00a7 Oikeus omaan kieleen ja kulttuuriin [...] Viittomakielt\u00e4 k\u00e4ytt\u00e4vien sek\u00e4 vammaisuuden vuoksi tulkitsemisja k\u00e4\u00e4nn\u00f6sapua tarvitsevien oikeudet turvataan lailla. (Ministry of Justice, Finland: [http://www.finlex.fi/linkit/ajansd/19990731000 ''Suomen perustuslaki''].)</ref>|||[http://www.om.fi/uploads/54begu60narbnv_1.pdf The Constitution of Finland]}}\n\n===Iceland===\n[[Icelandic Sign Language]] was recognised by law in education in 2004.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|This National Curriculum Guide contains, for the first time, provisions on special Icelandic instruction for students whose mother tongue is not Icelandic. There are also new provisions on special Icelandic instruction for deaf and hearing-impaired pupils and sign-language instruction for the deaf. The objectives for Icelandic instruction of immigrants and the deaf and of sign-language instruction fall under the subject area of language arts (Icelandic) in compulsory school. [...]\n\nSign language is of basic importance for the development of language, personality and thinking of deaf children. For the deaf, sign language is the most important source of knowledge and their route to participation in Icelandic culture and the culture of the deaf. Sign language is of great importance for all school work and for the pupils' life and work.<ref name=\"icelandic\">\u00cd a\u00f0aln\u00e1mskr\u00e1 grunnsk\u00f3la eru \u00ed fyrsta sinn sett \u00e1kv\u00e6\u00f0i um s\u00e9rstaka \u00edslenskukennslu fyrir nemendur me\u00f0 anna\u00f0 m\u00f3\u00f0urm\u00e1l en \u00edslensku. Einnig eru n\u00fd \u00e1kv\u00e6\u00f0i um s\u00e9rstaka \u00edslenskukennslu fyrir heyrnarlausa og heyrnarskerta nemendur og t\u00e1knm\u00e1lskennslu fyrir heyrnarlausa. Markmi\u00f0 fyrir \u00edslenskukennslu n\u00fdb\u00faa og heyrnarlausra og t\u00e1knm\u00e1lskennslu falla undir n\u00e1mssvi\u00f0 \u00edslensku \u00ed grunnsk\u00f3la. [...]\n\nT\u00e1knm\u00e1l hefur grundvallar\u00fe\u00fd\u00f0ingu fyrir \u00feroska m\u00e1ls, pers\u00f3nuleika og hugsunar heyrnarlausra nemenda. Hj\u00e1 heyrnarlausum er t\u00e1knm\u00e1li\u00f0 mikilv\u00e6gasta uppspretta \u00feekkingar og lei\u00f0 til a\u00f0 taka \u00fe\u00e1tt \u00ed \u00edslenskri menningu og menningu heyrnarlausra. T\u00e1knm\u00e1li\u00f0 hefur mikla \u00fe\u00fd\u00f0ingu fyrir alla vinnu \u00ed sk\u00f3lanum og fyrir l\u00edf og starf nemendanna. (Ministry of Education, Science and Culture: [http://bella.stjr.is/utgafur/AGalmennurhluti.pdf ''A\u00f0aln\u00e1mskr\u00e1 grunnsk\u00f3la: Almennur hluti''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927194051/http://bella.stjr.is/utgafur/AGalmennurhluti.pdf |date=2007-09-27 }})</ref>|||4=[http://bella.mrn.stjr.is/utgafur/general.pdf#page=23 The National Curriculum Guide for Compulsory School (Ministry of Education, Science and Culture, 2004)] (official translation)}}\n\nOn 27 May 2011, the Icelandic Parliament unanimously approved a bill which recognises Icelandic Sign Language as an official minority language with constitutional rights and as the first language of the deaf people of [[Iceland]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Indian subcontinent===\nThere is no official recognition of [[Indo-Pakistani Sign Language]] (IPSL), which is well-documented, widely used throughout the [[Indian subcontinent]] across national and state borders with few regional variations, and has over a million estimated users in [[India]] alone, is also commonly used in [[Pakistan]] and probably also in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Evans |first=Nicholas |title=Reciprocals and Semantic Typology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U020QQv1Qn4C&pg=PA95 |location=Amsterdam & Philadelphia |publisher=John Benjamins Publishing |page=95 |isbn=9789027206794 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Ireland===\nIrish Sign Language was given official recognition in 2017. The \"Recognition of Irish Sign Language for the Deaf Community Bill 2016\" passed all stages in the [[Oireachtas]] (Irish Parliament) on 14 December 2017, and was signed into law by the [[President of Ireland]] [[Michael D. Higgins|Michael D Higgins]] on 24 December 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/irish-sign-language-given-official-legal-recognition-1.3338081|title=Irish Sign Language given official legal recognition|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2017/1224/929482-sign-language-bill/|title=President signs Irish Sign Language bill into law|date=2017-12-24|work=RTE.ie|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en}}</ref> Prior to 2017, there was no automatic right for deaf people to have an ISL [[Language interpretation|interpreter]] (except for criminal court proceedings). For the deaf community, recognition of ISL means more legal rights and better access to [[public service]]s - including [[Education in the Republic of Ireland|education]], [[Healthcare in the Republic of Ireland|healthcare]], [[Media of the Republic of Ireland|media]] and [[banking]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2017/1213/927259-irish-sign-language/|title=D\u00e1il passes 'historic' sign language legislation|date=2017-12-14|work=RTE.ie|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/irish-sign-language-set-to-be-given-official-status-36407921.html|title=Irish Sign Language set to be given official status - Independent.ie|work=Independent.ie|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/irish-sign-language-set-to-receive-official-recognition-818648.html|title=Irish sign language set to receive official recognition|date=2017-12-14|work=Breaking News|access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref>\n\n===Italy===\nThere is no official recognition of [[Italian Sign Language]] (''Lingua dei Segni Italiana'', LIS) yet. Those who oppose LIS recognition say this language is \"grammarless,\" although, by definition, a [[Language#The properties of language|language]] cannot be, in fact, grammarless. Several research on the matter have already shown that [[Italian Sign Language]] is a proper language.<ref>[http://michelebrunelli.interfree.it/GrammLIS_e_Restrittive.pdf Michele Brunelli: Grammatica della LIS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722035622/http://michelebrunelli.interfree.it/GrammLIS_e_Restrittive.pdf |date=2011-07-22 }}</ref>\n\n===Kenya===\nThe 2010 [[Constitution of Kenya]] recognises [[Kenyan Sign Language]] and states that the state shall promote the development and use of Kenyan Sign Language (Article 7.3b). Sign language is recognised further in Article 120 (1) which states that 'the official languages of Parliament are [[Swahili language|Kiswahili]], [[English language|English]] and Kenyan Sign Language and the business of Parliament may be conducted in English, Kiswahili and Kenyan Sign Language.'<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://kenyalaw.org:8181/exist/kenyalex/actview.xql?actid=Const2010 |title=Constitution of Kenya, 2010 |work=Kenya Law |publisher=Judiciary of Kenya |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Malta ===\nThe [[Maltese Sign Language]] (LSM) was official recognized by parliament in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/63266/parliament_gives_maltese_sign_language_official_recognition|title=Parliament gives Maltese sign language official recognition}}</ref>\n\n=== Mexico ===\n\nThe [[Mexican Sign Language]] (LSM) was officially declared a \"national language\" in 2003, and it started being used in public deaf education thereafter.<ref>Ley Federal para las Personas con Discapacidad.  http://www.diputados.gob.mx/LeyesBiblio/pdf/262.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150616003344/http://www.diputados.gob.mx/LeyesBiblio/pdf/262.pdf |date=2015-06-16 }}</ref> Before 2003, deaf education in the country was focused on oralism (speech and lipreading) with few schools conducting classes in LSM.<ref>Karla Faurot, Dianne Dellinger, Andy Eatough, Steve Parkhurst (1992, revised 1998 and 2001) The identity of Mexican sign as a language. http://www.sil.org/silesr/2000/2000-002/ \u00a9 1999 Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\nAlthough [[Nepali Sign Language]] has not yet been officially recognized as the [[mother tongue]] of Nepal's deaf population, legislation is underway which will bring Nepali law in line with the provisions of the UN [[Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities]]. These laws will recognize the rights of the deaf to use [[Nepali Sign Language]] have it used in education, in social life, in the legal sphere, etc., and this should thus lead to official governmental recognition of [[Nepali Sign Language]] on a par with the various spoken languages of Nepal.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Netherlands===\n[[File:Nederlandse gebarentaal krijgt eindelijk een zichtbare plek in onze samenleving.webm|thumb|[[Roelof van Laar]] explaining the 2016 bill to recognise NGT]]\nThe [[Dutch Sign Language]] (NGT) has not been recognised officially by law. In 2010, the [[Christian Union (Netherlands)|Christian Union]] party introduced a bill to recognise NGT, but it did not pass.<ref name=\"AD2016\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.ad.nl/nieuws/erken-nederlandse-gebarentaal-als-officiele-taal~a5a253f6/ |title=Erken Nederlandse gebarentaal als offici\u00eble taal |publisher=Algemeen Dagblad |date=3 October 2016 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref>\nIn October 2016, this was followed by a bill from MPs [[Roelof van Laar]] ([[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour Party]]) and [[Carla Dik-Faber]] (Christian Union) for legal recognition of NGT as an official language.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2016/10/03/gebarentaal-moet-erkend-worden-als-officiele-taal-a1524573|title=PvdA en CU: erken gebarentaal als offici\u00eble taal|author=Beila Heilbron|publisher=NRC Handelsblad|date=3 October 2016 |language=nl}}</ref> After Van Laar's departure, MP [[Attje Kuiken]] (Labour Party) took over the bill in September 2019, while MP [[Jessica van Eijs]] ([[Democrats 66]]) joined Kuiken and Dik-Faber.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.eerstekamer.nl/behandeling/20190927/brief_lid_fractie_brief_van_de/document3/f=/vl29hrq7v1yn.pdf |title=Voorstel van wet van de leden Van Laar en Dik-Faber ter erkenning van Nederlandse gebarentaal (Wet erkenning Nederlandse gebarentaal) |author=Attje Kuiken & Carla Dik-Faber |work=Brief van de leden Kuiken en Dik-Faber |publisher=Senate of the Netherlands |date=27 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nos.nl/nieuwsuur/artikel/2300498-initiatiefwet-nederlandse-gebarentaal-erkennen-als-officiele-taal.html |title=Initiatiefwet: Nederlandse Gebarentaal erkennen als offici\u00eble taal |author=Linda de Groot |work=Nieuwsuur |publisher=NOS |date=5 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref> At the end of September 2019 the Advisory Division of the [[Council of State (Netherlands)|Council of State]] stated that the text of the bill was still too vague, as it did not make clear which problems it exactly intended to address and through which practical means; for example, it asked whether 'the Deaf culture' \u2013 mentioned in the bill \u2013 also needed to be legally recognised, as if so, what that term precisely entailed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.raadvanstate.nl/@117458/samenvatting-gebarentaal/ |title=Samenvatting advies initiatiefwetsvoorstel erkenning Nederlandse gebarentaal |publisher=Advisory Division of the Council of State |date=30 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\n[[New Zealand Sign Language]] became the third official language of [[New Zealand]] in April 2006, joining [[M\u0101ori language|English and M\u0101ori]] when the bill was passed in the New Zealand Parliament on 6 April 2006.<ref>McKee, R. 2007. The eyes have it! Our third official language\u2013New Zealand Sign Language. ''Journal of New Zealand Studies'', NS 4-5.129-148.</ref>\n\n{{cquote|Part 2 cl 6: New Zealand Sign Language is declared to be an official language of New Zealand.|||[http://www.odi.govt.nz/documents/nzds/nzsl-bill.pdf New Zealand Sign Language Bill]}}\n\n=== North Macedonia ===\nThe [[Macedonian Sign Language]] (''\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043d \u0458\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, Makedonski znakoven jazik'') is officially recognized as \"natural way of communication between the people\". The language is regulated by a law, which allows students and every individual in [[North Macedonia]] to study the language. Also, the law secures the right of interpreter for the students with special needs, and every other deaf person can request an interpreter, as well.<ref name=\"\u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\">''[http://www.deafmkd.org.mk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=57&Itemid=82&lang=mk \u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0437\u0430 \u0443\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \u043d\u0430  \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043e\u0442 \u0458\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0435\u043d \u0432\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430, \u0431\u0440\u043e\u0458 105, 21 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442 2009, \u0421\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0458\u0435]''</ref> Currently,{{when|date=April 2020}} there are more than 6.000 Macedonian citizens with deafness.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Northern Ireland===\nIn Northern Ireland, both [[British Sign Language]] and [[Irish Sign Language]] (but not [[Northern Ireland Sign Language]]) were recognised as official languages by the [[Northern Ireland Office]] in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nio.gov.uk/paul-murphy-announces-recognition-for-sign-language/media-detail.htm?newsID=8540 |title=Paul Murphy announces recognition for sign language |accessdate=2008-06-22 |date=2004-03-30 |publisher=[[Northern Ireland Office]] |quote=I am pleased to announce formal recognition for both British and Irish Sign Languages in Northern Ireland. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520115301/http://www.nio.gov.uk/paul-murphy-announces-recognition-for-sign-language/media-detail.htm?newsID=8540 |archivedate=2011-05-20 }}</ref> but they don't yet have the same status as the province's two official minority languages, [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[Ulster Scots language|Ulster-Scots]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Norway===\n[[Norwegian Sign Language]] is recognised by law in education.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Papua New Guinea===\nIn May 2015, [[Papua New Guinean Sign Language]] became the fourth official language of [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref name=\"sil.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sil.org/about/news/two-sign-languages-given-official-language-status|title=Two Sign Languages Given Official Language Status|date=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Philippines ===\nArticle 3 of Republic Act No. 11106 declared [[Filipino Sign Language]] as the national sign language of the [[Philippines]], specifying that it shall be recognized, supported and promoted as the medium of official communication in all transactions involving the deaf, and as the language of instruction of deaf education.<ref>{{cite act |url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/downloads/2018/10oct/20181030-RA-11106-RRD.pdf|title=The Filipino Sign Language Act|type=Republic act|number=11106|article=3|work=Official Gazette |publisher=Government of the Philippines|date=30 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Genalyn Kabiling |work=Manila Bulletin |title=Filipino Sign Language declared as nat\u2019l sign language of Filipino deaf |date=12 November 2018 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2018/11/12/filipino-sign-language-declared-as-natl-sign-language-of-filipino-deaf/ |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Portugal===\n{{cquote|Art. 74, 2 (h): In implementing the education policy, the state shall be charged with protecting and developing Portuguese sign language, as an expression of culture and an instrument for access to education and equal opportunities.<ref name=\"portuguese\">Na realiza\u00e7\u00e3o da pol\u00edtica de ensino incumbe ao Estado proteger e valorizar a l\u00edngua gestual portuguesa, enquanto express\u00e3o cultural e instrumento de acesso \u00e0 educa\u00e7\u00e3o e da igualdade de oportunidades. (Assembleia da Rep\u00fablica: [http://www.parlamento.pt/const_leg/crp_port/index.html Constitui\u00e7\u00e3o da rep\u00fablica portuguesa] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809203630/http://www.parlamento.pt/const_leg/crp_port/index.html |date=2007-08-09 }}</ref>|||[http://www.parlamento.pt/ingles/cons_leg/crp_ing/ Constitution of Portugal]}}\nAs an example, many shows (such as the news) in public channels ([[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]]) have one corner of the screen with a person translating what's being said into sign language.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n===Russia===\nRussian Sign Language (''\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0436\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a'') has very limited legal recognition. In accordance with the Federal \"Law on Protection of People with Disabilities\" the sign language is considered a language used for inter-personal communication only, which means that no state support for the language is provided.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\n=== Slovak Republic ===\n[[Slovak Sign Language]] was recognised in 1995 by law: \"Z\u00e1kon o posunkovej re\u010di nepo\u010duj\u00facich os\u00f4b 149/1995 Sb\" - the Law of the Sign Language of the Deaf 149/1995.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== South Africa ===\n[[South African Sign Language]] is not specifically recognised as a [[Languages of South Africa|Language of South Africa]] by the country's [[Constitution of South Africa|constitution]], instead it contains the phrase \"sign language\" in the generic sense.<ref>http://www.info.gov.za/documents/constitution/1996/96cons1.htm#6 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629092124/http://www.info.gov.za/documents/constitution/1996/96cons1.htm |date=2011-06-29 }}</ref>\nThere is a process underway in parliament to investigate the possibility of upgrading the status of SASL to become the country's 12th official language.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pmg.org.za/report/20091113-language-issues-proposed-recognition-south-african-sign-language-offi |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-10-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100515104619/http://www.pmg.org.za/report/20091113-language-issues-proposed-recognition-south-african-sign-language-offi |archive-date=2010-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\nOn 31 December 2015, the \"South Korean National Assembly passed legislation to recognize Korean Sign Language as one of Korea\u2019s official languages.\"<ref name=\"sil.org\"/>\n\n=== Spain ===\nOn 28 June 2007, Spanish and Catalan Sign Languages were recognised by the Spanish Parliament to be official languages in Spain. This recent legal development has opened a door to reinforced communication in the areas of healthcare, justice, education and MCM.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nSo far, the [[Autonomous communities of Spain|Autonomous Communities]] of [[Catalonia]], [[Andalusia]], and [[Valencia (autonomous community)|Valencia]] had granted the use of sign languages to the Deaf. In the other Spanish regions no sign languages were so far recognised, and support in terms of sign language interpretation for Deaf persons has been minimal or confined by different budgets. As pointed out, there are three sign languages claimed by Deaf organisations: [[Spanish Sign Language]], [[Catalan Sign Language]] (LSC) and [[Valencian Sign Language]] (LSPV), although some linguists consider these to be the same.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Catalonia====\nAlthough a regional law guarantees the presence of [[Catalan Sign Language]] since 1994 in all areas under the Catalan Government, such as education and media, until recently it was officially recognised the LSC in the [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia]] of 2006.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Andalusia====\nThe legal situation in Andalusia is similar to the one in Catalonia, where a regional Law guarantees the presence of the [[Spanish Sign Language]] (LSE) in all social scopes since 1998. Recently, a recognition of it is included in the reforming of their Statute of Autonomy. At the moment, Andalusia is the unique Community where LSE is recognised with regards to the rest of Spain. In any case, in linguistic terms, the LSE used there has a strong dialectal variation.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Valencia====\nUntil recently, Valencia had poor legal support for the Deaf. The approved 2006 Statute of Autonomy grants to Valencian Deaf their right to use [[Valencian Sign Language]] (LSPV or LSCV). (Though the statute refers only to \"sign language\" in a generic sense.){{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|Article 13,4: The Generalitat shall grant the use of the own sign language of deaf persons, which shall have to be purposed in education, protection and respect.<ref name=\"valencian\">La Generalitat garantir\u00e0 l\u2019\u00fas de la llengua de signes pr\u00f2pia de les persones sordes, que haur\u00e0 de ser objecte d\u2019ensenyament, protecci\u00f3 i respecte. (Corts Valencianes: [http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf Estatut d'Autonomia de la Communitat Valenciana] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926130504/http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf |date=2007-09-26 }}.)</ref>|||[http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf Statute of Autonomy of the Valencian Country]}}\n\n====Galicia====\n[[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] is said{{by whom|date=June 2012}} to be working on a bill concerning the recognition of a sign language.{{citation needed|date=June 2012}}\n\n=== Sri Lanka ===\nThe recognition of [[Sri Lankan sign languages|Sri Lankan Sign Language]] was accepted by [[Sri Lanka]] on 26 September 2010. According to the report by [[Sri Lanka]]n Newspaper at Internet on 23 September 2010[<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.colombopage.com/archive_10B/Sep23_1285222003KA.php|title = Sign language recognized in Sri Lanka|website = Colombo Page|date = 23 September 2010|location = Colombo, Sri Lanka}}</ref>]\n\n===Thailand===\n[[Thai Sign Language]] was acknowledged as \"the national language of deaf people in Thailand\" on 17 August 1999, in a resolution signed by the Permanent Secretary for Education on behalf of the Royal Thai Government that affirmed the rights of deaf people to learn this distinct sign language as their first language at home and in schools. According to a  [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231953/http://pr.gallaudet.edu/otg/BackIssues.asp?ID=3810 report by Charles Reilly (1999)], \"specific actions will be taken by the government, including hiring deaf people as teachers and instructors of sign language in deaf schools, and providing interpreters for deaf people in higher education.\"\n\n===Turkey===\nThere is currently{{when|date=April 2020}} no official recognition of the [[Turkish Sign Language]], the de facto sign language in use by the Turkish deaf community.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 1 July 2005, the [[Turkish Grand National Assembly]] enacted an updated [[disability discrimination act|Disability Law]] (No. 5378), which for the first time in Turkish law made references to sign language. Law no. 15 says that a sign language is to be used in the deaf education system, and law no. 30 says that sign language interpreting is to be provided to deaf people.<ref>http://majordomo.valenciacc.edu/hypermail/slling-l/0508/0013.html{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, these laws are yet to be implemented (as of 2007), and it remains to be seen what form of sign language, if any, will be supported. There has been some discussion in parliament about \"developing\" a standardised sign language.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abgs.gov.tr/tarama/tarama_files/19/SC19DET_People%20with%20disabilities.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2007-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070404073157/http://www.abgs.gov.tr/tarama/tarama_files/19/SC19DET_People%20with%20disabilities.pdf |archive-date=2007-04-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTurkey also has action plans for disability issues, such as the Employment of Disabled Persons Plan (2005\u20132010) and the Prevention of Discrimination Against Disabled Persons Plan (2006\u20132010).{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Uganda===\nOn 8 October 1995, [[Uganda]] adopted a new constitution that included a mention that 'The State shall [...] promote the development of a sign language for the deaf'.<ref>[[World Federation of the Deaf|WFD]] News, April 1996.</ref> It does not specify the [[Ugandan Sign Language]] as being the intented language. A Deaf signer, 27-year-old [[Alex Ndeezi]], was elected to [[Parliament of Uganda|parliament]] in 1996.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|XXIV (iii). The State shall [...] promote the development of a sign language for the deaf.\"|4=[http://www.parliament.go.ug/index.php?option=com_wrapper&Itemid=78 \"National Objectives and Directive Principles of State Policy\", Constitution of Uganda]}}\n\n===United States of America===\nThe Federal government does not recognize any language spoken or signed as an official language. However many individual states have laws recognizing [[American Sign Language]] as a \"foreign language\"; some recognize ASL as a language of instruction in schools.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} A number of U.S. universities accept ASL credit to fulfill foreign language requirements.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unm.edu/~wilcox/UNM/univlist.html |title=Universities That Accept ASL in Fulfillment of Foreign Language Requirements |publisher=University of New Mexico |last=Wilcox |first=Sherman}}</ref>\n\n===Uruguay===\n\nAlthough there are no \"official\" languages in Uruguay, nevertheless, Lengua de Se\u00f1as Uruguaya, or \"LSU\" (In English: \"Uruguayan Sign Language\"), was \"recognized\" as the language of deaf persons in 2001 by the law.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110704041632/http://200.40.229.134/IndexDB/Leyes/ConsultaLeyes.asp LEY No. 17.378.] ''Recon\u00f3cese a todos los efectos a la Lengua de Se\u00f1as Uruguaya como la lengua natural de las personas sordas y de sus comunidades en todo el territorio de la Rep\u00fablica.''  10 de Julio de 2001.  Parlamento del Uruguay.</ref>\n\nIn the 2008 law 18.437 (\"Ley General de Educaci\u00f3n. 12 de Diciembre de 2008\"), LSU is \"considered\" to be one of the mother tongues of Uruguayan citizens (along with Uruguayan Spanish and Uruguayan Portuguese. In the policy documents of the Comisi\u00f3n de Pol\u00edticas Ling\u00fc\u00edsticas en la Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica (the Public Education Language Policy Commission, which is part of the Administraci\u00f3n Nacional de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica, ANEP) it is proposed that LSU would be the principal language of deaf education.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Venezuela===\n[[Venezuelan Sign Language]] was recognised in the country's [[Constitution of Venezuela|constitution]] on 12 November 1999.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Zimbabwe===\nThe various [[Zimbabwean sign languages]], grouped together as \"sign language\", are recognised in the 2013 [[Constitution of Zimbabwe]] as one of the sixteen \"officially recognised languages of Zimbabwe\".<ref name=\"constitution\">\"The following languages, namely Chewa, Chibarwe, English, Kalanga, Koisan, Nambya, Ndau, Ndebele, Shangani, Shona, sign language, Sotho, Tonga, Tswana, Venda and Xhosa, are the officially recognised languages of Zimbabwe.\"  ([http://www.kubatana.net/docs/legisl/constitution_zim_draft_copac_130125.pdf Chapter 1, section 6, CONSTITUTION OF ZIMBABWE (final draft)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002110534/http://www.kubatana.net/docs/legisl/constitution_zim_draft_copac_130125.pdf |date=2013-10-02 }}).</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060216150733/http://fevlado.be/themas/gebarentaal/documenten/Status%20van%20gebarentalen%20in%20Europa.pdf Report on the status of Sign Languages in Europe] (PDF link)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050920061758/http://www.deafcouncil.org.uk/drcsub.htm Official Recognition of British Sign Language]\n\n{{sign language navigation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legal Recognition of Sign Languages}}\n[[Category:Sign language]]\n[[Category:Language policy]]\n", "name_user": "Nederlandse Leeuw", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNetherlands", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legal_recognition_of_sign_languages"}
{"title_page": "Nevsky Prospect", "text_new": "{{About|the main street of Saint Petersburg|the metro station|Nevsky Prospekt (Saint Petersburg Metro)|the story by Gogol|Nevsky Prospekt (story)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox street\n| name                    = Nevsky Prospect\n| native_name             =\n| caption                 = \n|image = {{Photomontage\n| photo1a = Spb 06-2012 Nevsky various 02.jpg\n| photo2a = Singer House SPB 01.jpg\n| photo2b = Eliseevs' House SPB 01.jpg\n| photo3a =  Anichkov Bridge SPB.jpg\n| photo3b = Grand Hotel Europe 4.jpg \n| photo4a = \u0421\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0446 (1).jpg\n| photo4b =\n| spacing = 2\n| color_border = white\n| color =  white\n| size = 276\n| foot_montage = Clockwise from top: [[Kazan Cathedral, Saint Petersburg|Kazan Cathedral]], [[Eliseyev Emporium (Saint Petersburg)|Eliseyev Emporium]], [[Grand Hotel Europe]], [[Stroganov Palace]], [[Anichkov Bridge]], [[Singer House]]\n}}\n| former_names            = 25 October Prospect\n| postal_code             = \n| addresses               =\n| length_mi               = \n| length_round            = \n| width                   = \n| location                = [[Saint Petersburg|St.&nbsp;Petersburg]]\n| client                  =\n| owner                   =\n| current_tenants         =\n| sector                  =\n| category                =\n| coordinates             = {{coord|59.9318|N|30.3528|E|source:wikidata|display=title,inline}}\n| commissioning_date      =\n| construction_start_date =\n| completion_date         =\n| inauguration_date       =\n| demolition_date         =\n| main_contractor         =\n| cost                    =\n}}\n\n[[File:Nevsky prospect in 1800.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The avenue near the [[Great Gostiny Dvor|Gostiny Dvor]], 1799<br />by [[Benjamin Patersen]].]]\n[[File:znamenka.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The avenue near the [[Moskovsky railway station (Saint Petersburg)|Nicholas Station]], 1890s]]\n'''Nevsky Prospect''' ({{lang-rus|\u041d\u0435\u0301\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0301\u043a\u0442|r=Nevsky [[Prospekt (street)|Prospekt]]|p=\u02c8n\u02b2\u025bfsk\u02b2\u026aj pr\u0250\u02c8sp\u02b2\u025bkt}}) is the [[main street]] ([[high street]]) in the federal city of [[Saint Petersburg|St.&nbsp;Petersburg]] in [[Russian Federation |  Russia]]. It takes its name from the [[Alexander Nevsky Lavra]], the monastery which stands at the eastern end of the street, and which in turn commemorates the Russian hero Prince Saint [[Alexander Nevsky]] (1221-1263). Following his founding of Saint Petersburg in 1703, Tsar [[Peter the Great | Peter I]] planned the course of the street as the beginning of the road to [[Veliky Novgorod| Novgorod]] and Moscow. The avenue runs from the [[Admiralty building, Saint Petersburg|Admiralty]] in the west to the [[Moskovsky railway station (Saint Petersburg) |Moscow Railway Station]] and, after veering slightly southwards at [[Vosstaniya Square]], to the Alexander Nevsky Lavra.\n\nMajor sights include the [[Francesco Bartolomeo Rastrelli| Rastrelliesque]] [[Stroganov Palace]], the huge [[Neoclassicism |neoclassical]] [[Kazan Cathedral, Saint Petersburg |Kazan Cathedral]], the [[Art Nouveau]] [[Singer House| ''Bookhouse'']] (originally the Singer House), [[Eliseyev Emporium (Saint Petersburg)| Elisseeff Emporium]], half a dozen 18th-century churches, a monument to [[Catherine the Great]], an enormous [[Great Gostiny Dvor| 18th-century shopping mall]], a [[Passage (department store)| mid-19th-century department store]], the [[National Library of Russia| Russian National Library]], and the [[Anichkov Bridge]] with its horse statues. \n\n[[Nikolai Gogol]] described the feverish life of the avenue in his story [[Nevsky Prospekt (story)| \"Nevsky Prospekt\"]], published in 1835. [[Fyodor Dostoevsky]] often employed Nevsky Prospekt as a setting in his works, such as ''[[Crime and Punishment]]'' (1866) and [[The Double (Dostoevsky novel)| ''The Double: A Petersburg Poem'']] (1846). The caf\u00e9-restaurant which the famous writers of the 19th-century [[Russian literature#Golden Age| Golden Age of the Russian literature]] frequented still remains as [[Literaturnoye Kafe (Saint Petersburg)| \"Literary Cafe\"]] on Nevsky Prospect.\n \nDuring the early Soviet years (1918\u201344) the name of Nevsky Prospect was changed, first and briefly to \"Proletkult Street\" ''(Ulitsa Proletkul'ta)'' in honor of [[Proletkult | that Soviet artistic organization]].<ref>Lynn Mally, ''Culture of the Future: The Proletkult Movement in Revolutionary Russia.''  Berkeley, CA: University of California Press, 1990; pg. 44.</ref> Following the demise of [[Proletkult]] already around 1920 the name was changed again, this time to \"Avenue of the 25th of October\", alluding to the day of the [[October Revolution]]: the name never took on in the daily language of the city's inhabitants who continued to use the pre-revolutionary name. During the [[siege of Leningrad]] (1941-1944) some walls on the north side of Nevsky Prospect were stencilled with the inscription \"[[Citizens! During shelling this side of the street is the most dangerous]]\", warning passers-by of the areas most at risk from German artillery bombardment.<ref name=\"YB\">{{cite web|first= Yan|last= Bratskiy|url= https://tvzvezda.ru/news/vstrane_i_mire/content/201811191309-kuqz.htm|title=\u0412 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435 \u0432\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044b \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u043d\u0430\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u00ab\u041f\u0440\u0438 \u0430\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0431\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0435 \u044d\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0443\u043b\u0438\u0446\u044b \u043d\u0430\u0438\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0435 \u043e\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0430\u00bb|date= 19 November 2018|accessdate= 1 May 2019|publisher= [[Zvezda (TV channel)|Zvezda]]|language= Russian}}</ref> In 1962 the inscription was recreated on school building No. 210 on Nevsky Prospect through the initiative of poet [[Mikhail Dudin]].<ref name=\"YB\"/><ref name=\"IS\">{{cite book|first= Inna Arkadevna|last= Soboleva|title= \u0423\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433|year= 2011|publisher= \u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u043e\u043c \"\u041f\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0440\"|isbn= 9785459003901|language= Russian|page= 132}}</ref> The inscription, and other examples across the city, are considered war memorials and are frequently the site of commemorations of the siege. In January 2019 [[Governor of Saint Petersburg]] [[Alexander Beglov]] laid flowers at the inscription on Nevsky Prospect.<ref name=\"AB\">{{cite web|url= https://www.5-tv.ru/news/237539/aleksandr-beglov-vozlozil-cvety-kpamatnoj-nadpisi-nanevskom-prospekte/|title= \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u0411\u0435\u0433\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b \u0446\u0432\u0435\u0442\u044b \u043a \u043f\u0430\u043c\u044f\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u041d\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0435|date= 26 January 2019|accessdate= 1 May 2019|publisher= 5-\u0420\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439|language= Russian}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the siege of Leningrad, in January 1944, the name ''Nevsky Prospect'' was formally restored and has remained ever since.<ref>http://www.hellopiter.ru/The_neva_prospectus.html</ref>\n\nThe Nevsky today functions as the main thoroughfare in [[Saint Petersburg]]. The majority of the city's shopping and nightlife takes place on or immediately off Nevsky Prospekt.\n\nThe street is served by the stations [[Admiralteyskaya (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Admiralteyskaya]], [[Nevsky Prospekt (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Nevsky Prospekt]], [[Gostiny Dvor (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Gostiny Dvor]], [[Mayakovskaya (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Mayakovskaya]], [[Ploshchad Vosstaniya (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Ploshchad Vosstaniya]] and [[Ploshchad Alexandra Nevskogo I (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Ploshchad Alexandra Nevskogo I]] of [[Saint Petersburg Metro]].<ref>\n[http://www.nevsky-prospekt.com/home.html Nevsky Prospekt] - \"The Prospekt has five Metro stations along its length, with each having its own unique identity. These are; \"Ploshchad Aleksandra Nevskogo\", \"Ploshchad Vosstaniya\", \"Mayakovskaya\", \"Gostinyy Dvor\" and \"Nevsky Prospekt\". A sixth station called 'Admiralty' has just been built on the M5 line just off Nevsky on Bolshaya Morskaya ul.\"\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of upscale shopping districts]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscat-inline|Nevsky Prospekt}}\n\n[[Category:Nevsky Prospekt| ]]\n[[Category:Shopping districts and streets in Russia]]\n[[Category:Streets in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Alexander Nevsky|Prospekt]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the main street of Saint Petersburg|the metro station|Nevsky Prospekt (Saint Petersburg Metro)|the story by Gogol|Nevsky Prospekt (story)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox street\n| name                    = Nevsky Prospect\n| native_name             =\n| caption                 = \n|image = {{Photomontage\n| photo1a = Spb 06-2012 Nevsky various 02.jpg\n| photo2a = Singer House SPB 01.jpg\n| photo2b = Eliseevs' House SPB 01.jpg\n| photo3a =  Anichkov Bridge SPB.jpg\n| photo3b = Grand Hotel Europe 4.jpg \n| photo4a = \u0421\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0446 (1).jpg\n| photo4b =\n| spacing = 2\n| color_border = white\n| color =  white\n| size = 276\n| foot_montage = Clockwise from top: [[Kazan Cathedral, Saint Petersburg|Kazan Cathedral]], [[Eliseyev Emporium (Saint Petersburg)|Eliseyev Emporium]], [[Grand Hotel Europe]], [[Stroganov Palace]], [[Anichkov Bridge]], [[Singer House]]\n}}\n| former_names            = 25 October Prospect\n| postal_code             = \n| addresses               =\n| length_mi               = \n| length_round            = \n| width                   = \n| location                = [[Saint Petersburg|St.&nbsp;Petersburg]]\n| client                  =\n| owner                   =\n| current_tenants         =\n| sector                  =\n| category                =\n| coordinates             = {{coord|59.9318|N|30.3528|E|source:wikidata|display=title,inline}}\n| commissioning_date      =\n| construction_start_date =\n| completion_date         =\n| inauguration_date       =\n| demolition_date         =\n| main_contractor         =\n| cost                    =\n}}\n\n[[File:Nevsky prospect in 1800.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The avenue near the [[Great Gostiny Dvor|Gostiny Dvor]], 1799<br />by [[Benjamin Patersen]].]]\n[[File:znamenka.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The avenue near the [[Moskovsky railway station (Saint Petersburg)|Nicholas Station]], 1890s]]\n'''Nevsky Prospect''' ({{lang-rus|\u041d\u0435\u0301\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0301\u043a\u0442|r=Nevsky [[Prospekt (street)|Prospekt]]|p=\u02c8n\u02b2\u025bfsk\u02b2\u026aj pr\u0250\u02c8sp\u02b2\u025bkt}}) is the [[main street]] ([[high street]]) in the federal city of [[Saint Petersburg|St.&nbsp;Petersburg]] in [[Russian Federation |  Russia]]. It takes its name from the [[Alexander Nevsky Lavra]], the monastery which stands at the eastern end of the street, and which in turn commemorates the Russian hero Prince Saint [[Alexander Nevsky]] (1221-1263). Following his founding of Saint Petersburg in 1703, Tsar [[Peter the Great | Peter I]] planned the course of the street as the beginning of the road to [[Veliky Novgorod| Novgorod]] and Moscow. The avenue runs from the [[Admiralty building, Saint Petersburg|Admiralty]] in the west to the [[Moskovsky railway station (Saint Petersburg) |Moscow Railway Station]] and, after veering slightly southwards at [[Vosstaniya Square]], to the Alexander Nevsky Lavra.\n\nMajor sights include the [[Francesco Bartolomeo Rastrelli| Rastrelliesque]] [[Stroganov Palace]], the huge [[Neoclassicism |neoclassical]] [[Kazan Cathedral, Saint Petersburg |Kazan Cathedral]], the [[Art Nouveau]] [[Singer House| ''Bookhouse'']], [[Eliseyev Emporium (Saint Petersburg)| Elisseeff Emporium]], half a dozen 18th-century churches, a monument to [[Catherine the Great]], an enormous [[Great Gostiny Dvor| 18th-century shopping mall]], a [[Passage (department store)| mid-19th-century department store]], the [[National Library of Russia| Russian National Library]], the [[Anichkov Bridge]] with its horse statues, and the [[Singer House]]. \n\n[[Nikolai Gogol]] described the feverish life of the avenue in his story [[Nevsky Prospekt (story)| \"Nevsky Prospekt\"]], published in 1835. [[Fyodor Dostoevsky]] often employed Nevsky Prospekt as a setting in his works, such as ''[[Crime and Punishment]]'' (1866) and [[The Double (Dostoevsky novel)| ''The Double: A Petersburg Poem'']] (1846). The caf\u00e9-restaurant which the famous writers of the 19th-century [[Russian literature#Golden Age| Golden Age of the Russian literature]] frequented still remains as [[Literaturnoye Kafe (Saint Petersburg)| \"Literary Cafe\"]] on Nevsky Prospect.\n \nDuring the early Soviet years (1918\u201344) the name of Nevsky Prospect was changed, first and briefly to \"Proletkult Street\" ''(Ulitsa Proletkul'ta)'' in honor of [[Proletkult | that Soviet artistic organization]].<ref>Lynn Mally, ''Culture of the Future: The Proletkult Movement in Revolutionary Russia.''  Berkeley, CA: University of California Press, 1990; pg. 44.</ref> Following the demise of [[Proletkult]] already around 1920 the name was changed again, this time to \"Avenue of the 25th of October\", alluding to the day of the [[October Revolution]]: the name never took on in the daily language of the city's inhabitants who continued to use the pre-revolutionary name. During the [[siege of Leningrad]] (1941-1944) some walls on the north side of Nevsky Prospect were stencilled with the inscription \"[[Citizens! During shelling this side of the street is the most dangerous]]\", warning passers-by of the areas most at risk from German artillery bombardment.<ref name=\"YB\">{{cite web|first= Yan|last= Bratskiy|url= https://tvzvezda.ru/news/vstrane_i_mire/content/201811191309-kuqz.htm|title=\u0412 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435 \u0432\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044b \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u043d\u0430\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u00ab\u041f\u0440\u0438 \u0430\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0431\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0435 \u044d\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0443\u043b\u0438\u0446\u044b \u043d\u0430\u0438\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0435 \u043e\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0430\u00bb|date= 19 November 2018|accessdate= 1 May 2019|publisher= [[Zvezda (TV channel)|Zvezda]]|language= Russian}}</ref> In 1962 the inscription was recreated on school building No. 210 on Nevsky Prospect through the initiative of poet [[Mikhail Dudin]].<ref name=\"YB\"/><ref name=\"IS\">{{cite book|first= Inna Arkadevna|last= Soboleva|title= \u0423\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433|year= 2011|publisher= \u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u043e\u043c \"\u041f\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0440\"|isbn= 9785459003901|language= Russian|page= 132}}</ref> The inscription, and other examples across the city, are considered war memorials and are frequently the site of commemorations of the siege. In January 2019 [[Governor of Saint Petersburg]] [[Alexander Beglov]] laid flowers at the inscription on Nevsky Prospect.<ref name=\"AB\">{{cite web|url= https://www.5-tv.ru/news/237539/aleksandr-beglov-vozlozil-cvety-kpamatnoj-nadpisi-nanevskom-prospekte/|title= \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u0411\u0435\u0433\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b \u0446\u0432\u0435\u0442\u044b \u043a \u043f\u0430\u043c\u044f\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u041d\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0435|date= 26 January 2019|accessdate= 1 May 2019|publisher= 5-\u0420\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439|language= Russian}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the siege of Leningrad, in January 1944, the name ''Nevsky Prospect'' was formally restored and has remained ever since.<ref>http://www.hellopiter.ru/The_neva_prospectus.html</ref>\n\nThe Nevsky today functions as the main thoroughfare in [[Saint Petersburg]]. The majority of the city's shopping and nightlife takes place on or immediately off Nevsky Prospekt.\n\nThe street is served by the stations [[Admiralteyskaya (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Admiralteyskaya]], [[Nevsky Prospekt (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Nevsky Prospekt]], [[Gostiny Dvor (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Gostiny Dvor]], [[Mayakovskaya (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Mayakovskaya]], [[Ploshchad Vosstaniya (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Ploshchad Vosstaniya]] and [[Ploshchad Alexandra Nevskogo I (Saint Petersburg Metro)| Ploshchad Alexandra Nevskogo I]] of [[Saint Petersburg Metro]].<ref>\n[http://www.nevsky-prospekt.com/home.html Nevsky Prospekt] - \"The Prospekt has five Metro stations along its length, with each having its own unique identity. These are; \"Ploshchad Aleksandra Nevskogo\", \"Ploshchad Vosstaniya\", \"Mayakovskaya\", \"Gostinyy Dvor\" and \"Nevsky Prospekt\". A sixth station called 'Admiralty' has just been built on the M5 line just off Nevsky on Bolshaya Morskaya ul.\"\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of upscale shopping districts]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscat-inline|Nevsky Prospekt}}\n\n[[Category:Nevsky Prospekt| ]]\n[[Category:Shopping districts and streets in Russia]]\n[[Category:Streets in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Alexander Nevsky|Prospekt]]\n", "name_user": "JSlip", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nevsky_Prospect"}
{"title_page": "Richard Louis Hunter", "text_new": "{{short description|American forger and serial killer}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name        = Richard Louis Hunter\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| alt         = \n| birth_name  = \n| alias       = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1955}}\n| birth_place = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| cause       = \n| conviction  = [[Murder]] x4<br>Rape x4<br>Burglary x4<br>[[Forgery]] x1\n| sentence    = [[Life imprisonment]]\n| victims     = 4\n| beginyear   = March\n| endyear     = April 1986\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| states      = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| apprehended = April 20, 1986\n| imprisoned  = \n}}\n'''Richard Louis Hunter'''<ref group=n>Middle name is also spelled 'Lewis'</ref> (born 1955) is a convicted [[United States|American]] [[serial killer]] and forger. A day laborer, Hunter raped and killed four elderly women in [[Atlanta]] between March and April 1986, robbing their apartments afterwards. He later plead guilty to the murders and numerous robberies, and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]].<ref name=term>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41657911/hunter-pleads-guilty-1/|title=Man gets 8 life terms in stranglings|author=Gary Hendricks|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 6, 1987}}</ref>\n\n==Murders==\nThe first victim was 85-year-old Annie Rochelle Copeland, who lived alone in a small apartment in southwest Atlanta. She was found by a neighbor, a [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]], on March 1, 1986, who got worried after knocking on the door and receiving no reply. She was found lying on her bed in the fetal position, covered with a bedspread and blanket, and her face covered by a pillow and her blue nightgown. The apartment had been turned upside down, with items from a pocketbook strewn about and a bloody pillowcase placed between her legs. The perpetrator had managed to enter by cutting the screen of a living room window and pulling out the windowpane.<ref name=sly>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653775/richard-lewis-hunter-victims-and-early/|title=Slayings|author=Bill Montgomery|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 12, 1986}}</ref> The killing scared other elderly residents living near [[Clark University]], who took additional measures to protect themselves in case the perpetrator struck again.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41652736/annie-rochelle-copeland-richard-hunter/|title=Police believe robbery motive in women's killing|author=David Corvette|publisher=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=March 2, 1986}}</ref>\n\nOnly a few days later, on March 6, 25-year-old Felton Clements went to check on his 61-year-old mother Aretha, who lived alone in northwest Atlanta, only to find her dead and her apartment ransacked. Mrs. Clements had been manually strangled and then wrapped up in her bedspread, nightgown disarranged, her head put against the foot of the bed and her right leg beneath her. Her plants had been overturned, her drawers emptied, with the killer then stealing her 25-inch color TV set and a pocketbook.<ref name=sly/> There were no suspects in this case either, as Aretha rarely left her home, except when visiting her best friend or for treatment at [[Grady Memorial Hospital]].<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41652957/aretha-clements-hunter-victim/|title=Son finds mother, 61, slain at her small apartment|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 7, 1986}}</ref>\n\nThe situation repeated on March 11, with the discovery of the body of 62-year-old Dena Mae Mike, a blind woman who hasn't been seen in two days.<ref name=hunt>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653182/dena-mae-mike-pt1-hunter/|title=Police hunt link in slayings of 3 elderly women|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 12, 1986}}</ref> Similarly to Copeland and Clements, she had either been smothered, and several objects had been placed on her head, including a sweater, a pillow, a plastic garment bag with clothing on hangers and a duffel bag. Like Copeland, her nightgown had been trampled with, and a bloody pillowcase was found between her legs.<ref name=sly/> Her killer had apparently entered through a kitchen window.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653225/dena-mike-murder-by-hunter-pt2/|title=Slayings|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 12, 1986}}</ref> With Mike's death, law enforcement from Atlanta Homicide began to make connections between the recent murders: all of the victims had been elderly black women, living alone off [[Social Security (United States)|social security benefits]], within one general area, and all had had their apartments burgled and items stolen after death. The [[Georgia Bureau of Investigation|GBI]] was involved in the investigations, and residents of the area were querried about any suspicious individuals in the area.<ref name=hunt/>\n\nFor the following weeks, the murders suddenly ceased, before abruptly resuming with the killing of 65-year-old Grace Hill on April 9. She was found by her friends, partially naked, on her living room floor in northwest Atlanta, suffocated to death and signs of possible sexual assault. The killer, whom had entered through an unlocked back door, had put a newspaper over her chest, and a doll between her legs.<ref name=sly/> With her death, the authorities officially announced to the media that they were investigating all four deaths as the doings of a serial killer.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653358/grace-hill-4th-victim-of-hunter/|title=Fourth elderly women found dead|publisher=[[Hawaii Tribune-Herald]]|date=April 10, 1986}}</ref>\n\n===Community response and perpetrator profile===\nThe murders caused a great stir in the city, including among politicians and community leaders, with then-Governor [[Joe Frank Harris]] offering a total of $8,000 reward for any information regarding the murders. Comparisons were also drawn to the [[Atlanta murders of 1979\u20131981]], albeit most of the victims were younger males.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653503/richard-hunter-victim-similarities/|title=Elderly westside victims lived, died in poverty and isolation|author=Bill Montgomery|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 12, 1986}}</ref> According to Dr. James Alan Fox, the killer was black, in his 30s, and lived near the victims, additionally theorizing that he was a sadist and that he might've developed a hatred for the elderly due to an abusive childhood.<ref name=sly/>\n\n==Arrest, trial and imprisonment==\nIn mid-April, an anonymous tip was received by police about a certain felon who should be investigated for the series. On April 20, the authorities arrested that suspect, who was residing in his girlfriend's house with their four children, on a probation violation - a 31-year-old convicted forger named Richard Louis Hunter, who had lived in the neighborhood.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654074/richard-lewis-hunter-arrested/|title=Suspect Arrested in Slayings of Elderly|publisher=[[Pharos-Tribune]]|date=April 24, 1986}}</ref><ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41657988/hunter-pleads-2/|title=Man gets 8 life terms in stranglings, page 2|author=Gary Hendricks|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 6, 1987}}</ref> Hunter was quickly ordered to undergo psychological tests at Grady Memorial Hospital, and was arraigned for court on May 8.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654182/hunter-to-be-psych-tested/|title=Accused killer must undergo tests|publisher=The Daily Spectrum|date=April 24, 1986}}</ref> On May 10, he was charged with the murder while sitting in the Atlanta city jail.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654342/richard-hunter-indicted-for-4-slayings/|title=Hunter is indicted in all four slayings of elderly black women|author=James Alexander Jr.|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 10, 1986}}</ref> Although officials deterred from saying how strong there was evidence against Hunter was, one anonymous source claimed that they had strong fingerprints matching those of the accused, who had already admitted to attempting to sell Copeland's TV set, but also claimed to have had an accomplice.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654374/hunter-indicted-for-4-murders/|title=Hunter|author=James Alexander Jr.|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 10, 1986}}</ref> Eventually, in order to avoid the [[death penalty]], Hunter plead guilty to the murders, and received 8 life sentences, plus 80 years for the burglaries associated with the killings. According to District Attorney Lewis R. Slaton, he would have to serve at least 30 years before being eligible for parole.<ref name=term/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Atlanta murders of 1979\u20131981]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://serialdispatches.com/hunter-richard-lewis/ Serial Dispatches article]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Richard Louis}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of rape]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:People convicted of burglary]]\n[[Category:People convicted of forgery]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:People from Atlanta]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American forger and serial killer}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name        = Richard Louis Hunter\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| alt         = \n| birth_name  = \n| alias       = \n| birth_date  = 1955\n| birth_place = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| cause       = \n| conviction  = [[Murder]] x4<br>Rape x4<br>Burglary x4<br>[[Forgery]] x1\n| sentence    = [[Life imprisonment]]\n| victims     = 4\n| beginyear   = March\n| endyear     = April 1986\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| states      = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| apprehended = April 20, 1986\n| imprisoned  = \n}}\n'''Richard Louis Hunter'''<ref group=n>Middle name is spelled 'Lewis'</ref> (born 1955) is a convicted [[United States|American]] [[serial killer]] and forger. A day laborer, Hunter raped and killed four elderly women in [[Atlanta]] between March and April 1986, robbing their apartments afterwards. He later plead guilty to the murders and numerous robberies, and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]].<ref name=term>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41657911/hunter-pleads-guilty-1/|title=Man gets 8 life terms in stranglings|author=Gary Hendricks|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 6, 1987}}</ref>\n\n==Murders==\nThe first victim was 85-year-old Annie Rochelle Copeland, who lived alone in a small apartment in southwest Atlanta. She was found by a neighbor, a [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]], on March 1, 1986, who got worried after knocking on the door and receiving no reply. She was found lying on her bed in the fetal position, covered with a bedspread and blanket, and her face covered by a pillow and her blue nightgown. The apartment had been turned upside down, with items from a pocketbook strewn about and a bloody pillowcase placed between her legs. The perpetrator had managed to enter by cutting the screen of a living room window and pulling out the windowpane.<ref name=sly>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653775/richard-lewis-hunter-victims-and-early/|title=Slayings|author=Bill Montgomery|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 12, 1986}}</ref> The killing scared other elderly residents living near [[Clark University]], who took additional measures to protect themselves in case the perpetrator struck again.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41652736/annie-rochelle-copeland-richard-hunter/|title=Police believe robbery motive in women's killing|author=David Corvette|publisher=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=March 2, 1986}}</ref>\n\nOnly a few days later, on March 6, 25-year-old Felton Clements went to check on his 61-year-old mother Aretha, who lived alone in northwest Atlanta, only to find her dead and her apartment ransacked. Mrs. Clements had been manually strangled and then wrapped up in her bedspread, nightgown disarranged, her head put against the foot of the bed and her right leg beneath her. Her plants had been overturned, her drawers emptied, with the killer then stealing her 25-inch color TV set and a pocketbook.<ref name=sly/> There were no suspects in this case either, as Aretha rarely left her home, except when visiting her best friend or for treatment at [[Grady Memorial Hospital]].<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41652957/aretha-clements-hunter-victim/|title=Son finds mother, 61, slain at her small apartment|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 7, 1986}}</ref>\n\nThe situation repeated on March 11, with the discovery of the body of 62-year-old Dena Mae Mike, a blind woman who hasn't been seen in two days.<ref name=hunt>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653182/dena-mae-mike-pt1-hunter/|title=Police hunt link in slayings of 3 elderly women|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 12, 1986}}</ref> Similarly to Copeland and Clements, she had either been smothered, and several objects had been placed on her head, including a sweater, a pillow, a plastic garment bag with clothing on hangers and a duffel bag. Like Copeland, her nightgown had been trampled with, and a bloody pillowcase was found between her legs.<ref name=sly/> Her killer had apparently entered through a kitchen window.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653225/dena-mike-murder-by-hunter-pt2/|title=Slayings|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 12, 1986}}</ref> With Mike's death, law enforcement from Atlanta Homicide began to make connections between the recent murders: all of the victims had been elderly black women, living alone off [[Social Security (United States)|social security benefits]], within one general area, and all had had their apartments burgled and items stolen after death. The [[Georgia Bureau of Investigation|GBI]] was involved in the investigations, and residents of the area were querried about any suspicious individuals in the area.<ref name=hunt/>\n\nFor the following weeks, the murders suddenly ceased, before abruptly resuming with the killing of 65-year-old Grace Hill on April 9. She was found by her friends, partially naked, on her living room floor in northwest Atlanta, suffocated to death and signs of possible sexual assault. The killer, whom had entered through an unlocked back door, had put a newspaper over her chest, and a doll between her legs.<ref name=sly/> With her death, the authorities officially announced to the media that they were investigating all four deaths as the doings of a serial killer.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653358/grace-hill-4th-victim-of-hunter/|title=Fourth elderly women found dead|publisher=[[Hawaii Tribune-Herald]]|date=April 10, 1986}}</ref>\n\n===Community response and perpetrator profile===\nThe murders caused a great stir in the city, including among politicians and community leaders, with then-Governor [[Joe Frank Harris]] offering a total of $8,000 reward for any information regarding the murders. Comparisons were also drawn to the [[Atlanta murders of 1979\u20131981]], albeit most of the victims were younger males.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653503/richard-hunter-victim-similarities/|title=Elderly westside victims lived, died in poverty and isolation|author=Bill Montgomery|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 12, 1986}}</ref> According to Dr. James Alan Fox, the killer was black, in his 30s, and lived near the victims, additionally theorizing that he was a sadist and that he might've developed a hatred for the elderly due to an abusive childhood.<ref name=sly/>\n\n==Arrest, trial and imprisonment==\nIn mid-April, an anonymous tip was received by police about a certain felon who should be investigated for the series. On April 20, the authorities arrested that suspect, who was residing in his girlfriend's house with their four children, on a probation violation - a 31-year-old convicted forger named Richard Louis Hunter, who had lived in the neighborhood.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654074/richard-lewis-hunter-arrested/|title=Suspect Arrested in Slayings of Elderly|publisher=[[Pharos-Tribune]]|date=April 24, 1986}}</ref><ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41657988/hunter-pleads-2/|title=Man gets 8 life terms in stranglings, page 2|author=Gary Hendricks|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 6, 1987}}</ref> Hunter was quickly ordered to undergo psychological tests at Grady Memorial Hospital, and was arraigned for court on May 8.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654182/hunter-to-be-psych-tested/|title=Accused killer must undergo tests|publisher=The Daily Spectrum|date=April 24, 1986}}</ref> On May 10, he was charged with the murder while sitting in the Atlanta city jail.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654342/richard-hunter-indicted-for-4-slayings/|title=Hunter is indicted in all four slayings of elderly black women|author=James Alexander Jr.|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 10, 1986}}</ref> Although officials deterred from saying how strong there was evidence against Hunter was, one anonymous source claimed that they had strong fingerprints matching those of the accused, who had already admitted to attempting to sell Copeland's TV set, but also claimed to have had an accomplice.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654374/hunter-indicted-for-4-murders/|title=Hunter|author=James Alexander Jr.|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 10, 1986}}</ref> Eventually, in order to avoid the [[death penalty]], Hunter plead guilty to the murders, and received 8 life sentences, plus 80 years for the burglaries associated with the killings. According to District Attorney Lewis R. Slaton, he would have to serve at least 30 years before being eligible for parole.<ref name=term/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Atlanta murders of 1979\u20131981]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://serialdispatches.com/hunter-richard-lewis/ Serial Dispatches article]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Richard Louis}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of rape]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:People convicted of burglary]]\n[[Category:People convicted of forgery]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:People from Atlanta]]\n", "name_user": "Haunted Spy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_